{"title_page": "S. P. Jain Institute of Management and Research", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox university\n |name              = SP Jain Institute of Management and Research\n |image             = S. P. Jain Institute of Management and Research logo.svg\n |motto             = {{lang-sa|\u0905\u092e\u0943\u0924\u0902 \u0924\u0941 \u0935\u093f\u0926\u094d\u092f\u093e}}\n |mottoeng          = Knowledge is Nectar\n |established       = {{Start date and age|1981}}\n |type              = [[Private school#India|Private]] [[business school]]\n |dean              = Ranjan Banerjee<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spjimr.org/newsroom/pressnotes/dr-ranjan-banner-takes-over-as-new-dean.asp|title=Press Notes - Dr.Ranjan Banerjee takes over as the Dean of SPJIMR|work=spjimr.org}}</ref>\n |students          = \n |city              = [[Mumbai]]\n |state             = [[Maharashtra]]\n |country           = [[India]]\n |campus            = [[Andheri]] (Urban area)\n |website           = [http://www.spjimr.org spjimr.org] \n |affiliations      = [[Association of Indian Universities|AIU]], [[Association of MBAs|AMBA]], [[AACSB]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/services/education/spjimr-earns-aacsb-international-accreditation/articleshow/66847736.cms|title=SPJIMR earns AACSB International Accreditation|last=|first=|date=28 Nov 2018|work=[[The Economic Times]]|access-date=9 Feb 2019|archive-url=https://archive.fo/n0ZVr|archive-date=9 Feb 2019|language=English}}</ref>\n }}\n'''S.P. Jain Institute of Management and Research''' ('''SPJIMR''') is a [[Private school#India|private]] [[business school]] affiliated under [[Bharatiya Vidya Bhavan]]. SPJIMR sits on a 45-acre campus in the western suburbs of [[Andheri]] in [[Mumbai]]. The Institute has an annual intake of approximately 700 students under various educational programmes with the [[Post Graduate Diploma in Management]] (PGDM) being the institution's oldest offered course.\n\n== History ==\n\nInaugurated in 1981 by the then British Prime Minister, [[Margaret Thatcher]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.margaretthatcher.org/document/104629|title= Speech by Margaret Thatcher at the inauguration|work=margaretthatcher.org}}</ref> SPJIMR had modest beginnings as a small extension of the campus of [[Bharatiya Vidya Bhavan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhavans.info/|title=bhavans.info|work=bhavans.info}}</ref> The institute was named after [[Shreyans Prasad Jain|Sahu Shreyans Prasad Jain]] of the [[Sahu Jain]] family, who financed the institution in its early years. At the time of its establishment, SPJIMR was among the three business schools in Mumbai.<ref name=\"discover_spjim\">{{cite web|url=http://www.spjimr.org/discover_spjimr/discover_spjimr.asp|title=Discover SPJIMR - S P Jain Institute of Management & Research, Mumbai|work=spjimr.org}}</ref> After financing from the Sahu Jain family stopped, the institute disaffiliated itself from [[Bombay University]] to provide itself with more freedom in curriculum decision-making and pedagogy design.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spjimr.org/discover_spjimr/discover_spjimr.asp|title= Introduction|work=spjimr.org}}</ref> SPJIMR is a part of the Bharatiya Vidya Bhavan and operates out of its campus at Munshi Nagar, Dadabhai Road, Andheri West, Mumbai.\n\n== Academics ==\n{{copyedit section|for=Per [[WP:UNIGUIDE]], programmes should not be listed. This should be summarized as an \"Academics\" section.|date=February 2020}}\n[[File:SPJIMR classroom 2008.jpg|thumb|A lecture hall at SPJIMR]]\n\n===Post Graduate Diploma in Management===\nSPJIMR's Post Graduate Diploma in Management (PGDM)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spjimr.org/pgdm/program-overview.aspx|title=PGDM programme Overview - Post Graduate Diploma in Management Programme (PGDM) - Equivalent to 2 Year Full Time MBA - SPJIMR, Mumbai|work=spjimr.org}}</ref> is a two-year full-time residential programme equivalent to an MBA. The programme offers specializations in Finance, Operations, Marketing and Information Management. The programme has consistently been ranked among the top 10 in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bschools.businesstoday.in/?year=2014&college=SPJIMR-Mumbai&rank=5|title= 'India's Best Business Schools' by Business Today|work=businesstoday.in}}</ref> It is accredited by [[AICTE]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spjimr.org/discover_spjimr/accreditations_and_achievements.asp|title=SPJIMR - Accreditations and Achievements|work=spjimr.org}}</ref>\nThe programme has seen much pedagogical experimentation over the years, including social projects and business plans,<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.rediff.com/money/2006/jun/28mnc.htm | title = Fortune 500 co to support Mumbai slum | date = 28 June 2006| publisher = [[Rediff.com]] | accessdate = 4 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url =  http://www.financialexpress.com/news/social-projects-spjimr-alumni/72131/ |  title = Social Projects: SPJIMR Alumni | date = 23 December 2003 | publisher = [[The Financial Express (India)|The Financial Express]] | accessdate = 4 January 2010}}</ref> use of theatre to learn management,<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.telegraphindia.com/1071223/jsp/7days/story_8700287.jsp | title = All the B-world's a stage | publisher = [[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] | location = [[Calcutta]] | date = 23 December 2007 | accessdate = 4 January 2010 }}</ref> Assessment and Development of Managerial Potential (ADMAP, a programme where students participate in the administration of the college)<ref>{{cite news | title = Self-Reliance \u2013 SPJIMR Saga: S.P. Jain Institute of Management combines management studies with social responsibilities | publisher = India Business Insight | date = 8 June 2003 }}</ref> and India-specific [[case method|cases]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.business-standard.com/india/news/studying-sonia/242249/ | title = Studying Sonia | author = Kalpana Pathak | publisher = Business Standard | date = 6 April 2006 | accessdate = 4 January 2010}}</ref> SPJIMR does not have a traditional summer internship projects like most other Indian B-schools.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.expressindia.com/news/fe/daily/19990411/fle11079.html | title = Self-study at SPJIMR this season | author = Nivedita Mookerji | date = 11 April 1999 | accessdate = 4 January 2010 | publisher = [[The Indian Express]]}}</ref> Instead, the students are required to work with NGOs in the rural areas during the summer; corporate internships happen during autumn instead.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.financialexpress.com/printer/news/79268/ | title = Mumbai-based B-schools Go Beyond Summer Projects | date = 1 April 2003 | accessdate = 4 January 2004 | publisher = [[The Financial Express (India)|The Financial Express]]}}</ref>\n\n===Post Graduate Programme in Management===\nThe Post Graduate Programme in Management (PGPM), formerly known as Post Graduate Diploma in Management (PGDM), is a 15-month (3 months of foundation courses through web learning), full-time residential programme accredited by the [[Association of MBAs]].<ref name=\"pgpm_ad\">{{cite web|url=http://epaper.timesofindia.com/Default/Scripting/ArticleWin.asp?From=Archive&Source=Page&Skin=ETNEW&BaseHref=ETM/2009/06/08&PageLabel=3&ForceGif=true&EntityId=Ad00308&ViewMode=HTML&GZ=T|title=Article Window|work=timesofindia.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.telegraphindia.com/1060928/asp/careergraph/story_6800326.asp | title = Short haul MBA | date = 28 September 2006 | publisher = [[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] | location = [[Calcutta]] | accessdate = 4 January 2010}}</ref> and AICTE.<ref name=\"spjimr.org\">https://www.spjimr.org/pgpm/programme</ref> It offers specialisations in [[Marketing Management|Marketing]], Finance, [[Operations Management|Operations and Supply Chain]], and [[Information Management]]. The course includes a stint at partner foreign universities such as [[Cornell University]], Michigan State University and Texas University as part of the specialization phase. The specializations are chosen at the time of admission. The program admits working professionals with a minimum of 5 years of professional experience from domains and leading industries to enable knowledge sharing and peer learning.  The course starts in January and ends in December.\n\n===Global Management Programme===\nThe Global Management Programme (GMP) which was previously called the Post Graduate Certificate in International Management (PGCIM) is a full-time residential MBA program with an international focus. As a part of this program, students complete the first 8 months of their studies in SPJIMR, Mumbai and then complete their international stint at a partner university. This program was started by the Center of Indo European Business Studies(CIEBS) which was funded by the European Union.<ref name=\"pgcim\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ciebs.de/|title=Startseite - CIEBS: Centre for Indio-European Business Studies|author=ESB Business School Reutlingen University|date=5 February 2015|work=ciebs.de}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"pgcim_overview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.spjimr.org/pgcim/pgcim-overview.aspx|title=International MBA Program from Top Business Schools at SPJIMR, Mumbai India|work=spjimr.org}}</ref> The MBA program requires a minimum of 3 years of work experience; students with prior international exposure are preferred.\n\n===Executive Management Programme===\nThe Executive Management Programme (EMP) is a non-residential programme, for working professionals, similar to an [[Master of Business Administration|EMBA]], with 60 full-day classes on campus, spread over 21 months and contact sessions. The programme considers graduates with minimum five years of experience, and mandates the support of the candidate's company.<ref name=\"spjimr_emp\">[http://www.spjimr.org/emba/emba_home.asp EMBA Home] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080930030707/http://www.spjimr.org/emba/emba_home.asp |date=30 September 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===Family Managed Business programme===\nThe Family Managed Business (FMB) program is designed for candidates to lead their [[family business]]es. The duration of the program is two years and includes a foreign visit. The participants spent a week at the institute to learn and the remaining three weeks of the month at their workplace. The duration of the Owner Manager Programme is twelve months. Selection requires sponsorship from the business, a test, and a personal interview. The degree awarded is a Post Graduate Programme in Management.<ref>http://spjimr.org/sites/default/files/AICTE%20Approval%20-%202017-2018.pdf\n\nhttps://insideiim.com/spjimr-launch-of-fellow-programme-in-management/\n\nhttp://businessworld.in/article/SPJIMR-Imparting-360-Degree-Education/11-11-2016-108121/\n\nhttps://www.flipsnack.com/SPJIMR/spjimr-news-sep-16.html?b=1&p=50\n</ref>\n\n'''Post Graduate Management Programme in Development Management (PGPDM)'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spjimr.org/pgpdm|title=Academic Why PGPDM {{!}} SPJIMR|website=spjimr.org|language=en|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref> \n\nIn SPJIMR\u2019s endeavour to enable \u201cfor-profit\u201d business management practices in the exponentially growing 'not-for-profit' sector, '''[https://spjimr.org/cedss CEdSS]''' offers '''PGPDM -''' A specialized executive management programme, for professionals working in the Social Development Sector including '''NGOs''', '''Corporate- CSRs''', '''Social Enterprises''' and people who do career transition. It is an 18 months modular program where participants come on campus for 6-8 days every 2 months, for the remaining 7 weeks they apply the learning to their organizational setting and undertake distant learning. PGDM is accredited by AMBA, one of the top three UK based global accreditation bodies which denote the highest standard of achievement in postgraduate business education as a unique program globally.\n\n'''Post Graduate Management Programme for Women (PGMPW)''' In 2016, SPJIMR launched the Post Graduate Management Programme for Women (PGMPW), targeted especially at women who have taken a break of more than two years after working in business roles. The 11-month full-time program seeks to prepare participants to return to a full-time career in senior managerial and leadership roles. \n<ref>http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/industry/services/education/sp-jain-institute-of-management-and-research-launches-management-programme-for-women/articleshow/53965438.cms\n\nhttp://www.ptinews.com/pressrelease/20175_press-subSPJIMR-Launches-a-Management-Programme-for-Women-Aspiring-to-Return-to-the-Workforce\n\nhttp://womanatwork.in/blog/sp-jain-institute-of-management-and-research-launches-management-programme-for-women/\n</ref>\n\n'''Fellow Programme in Management (FPM)'''\nSPJIMR launched a Fellow Programme in Management (FPM) in 2016 with an approved intake of five participants every year.  Participants of the FPM, which is a full-time doctoral-level program, undertake guided research in their chosen area of management studies after completing the prescribed coursework and are awarded as \u201cFellow of SPJIMR\u201d on successful completion of the program.<ref>http://spjimr.org/sites/default/files/AICTE%20Approval%20-%202017-2018.pdf\n\nhttps://insideiim.com/spjimr-launch-of-fellow-programme-in-management/\n\nhttp://businessworld.in/article/SPJIMR-Imparting-360-Degree-Education/11-11-2016-108121/ \nhttps://www.flipsnack.com/SPJIMR/spjimr-news-sep-16.html?b=1&p=50\n</ref>\n===Other programmes===\nSPJIMR offers several short term programs. Some of these are:  Start Your Business program (SYB) aimed at budding entrepreneurs, Grow Your Business program (GYB) to help meet the common challenges faced by small business owners and a program in Strategic Media & Entertainment Management (PSMEM) conducted in partnership with the Times Centre for Learning Ltd. (TCLL).<ref>http://www.prnewswire.co.in/news-releases/more-start-ups-led-by-spjimr-alumni-attract-funding-609871325.html</ref> SPJIMR runs several Management Development Programmes (MDPs), some of which are in areas like Leadership, Supply Chain Analytics, HR, IT Strategic Planning, Design Thinking and Analytics in Marketing. The PMP Certificate Preparatory program, the Advanced Project Management, and Agile Project Management programs are offered as part of Project Management group of programs.<ref>http://epaperbeta.timesofindia.com/Article.aspx?eid=31804&articlexml=Times-Group-launches-strategic-media-mgmt-course-with-17032017022034\n\n</ref>\n\n==Rankings==\n{{Infobox India university ranking\n|type=Institute\n| NIRF_B_2019 = 16\n| BT_2019 = 4\n| OUTLOOK_B_2018 = 6\n| QS_B_2019 = 201+\n| QS_B_A_2019 = 18\n}}\nGlobally, The ''[[Quacquarelli Symonds|QS]] Global 250 MBA Rankings 2019'' ranked SPJIMR 201+ in the world<ref name=Rankings_QS_B_2019/> and 18 in Asia.<ref name=Rankings_QS_B_A_2019/>\n\nIn India, SPJIMR was ranked 16 among management schools by the [[National Institutional Ranking Framework]] (NIRF) in 2019,<ref name=Rankings_NIRF_B_2019/> fourth by ''[[Business Today (India)|Business Today]]''{{'}}s \"India's best B-schools 2019\"<ref name=Rankings_BT_2019 /> and sixth in India by ''[[Outlook India]]''{{'}}s \"Top 100 Management Schools\" of 2018.<ref name=Rankings_OUTLOOK_B_2018 />\n\n== Lock, Stock & Trade ==\nLock, Stock & Trade is an annual national-level  mock investment game organised by SPJIMR in association with the [[National Entrepreneurship Network]] (NEN).<ref>[http://www.thehindubusinessline.in/bline/2005/09/28/stories/2005092802210800.htm S.P. Jain's new programme to groom students]. ''[[The Hindu]]''. 25 September 2008.</ref>\n\n== Accreditation ==\n\nThe [[Association of MBAs]] (AMBA) has accorded accreditation to SPJIMR's two-year PGDM, one-year PGPM and the Executive Management Programme (EMP).<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.mbaworld.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=474&Itemid=132 | title = Accredited MBA Programmes | publisher = AMBA | accessdate = 4 January 2010}}</ref> The PGDM programme is approved by [[AICTE]] and received \"A\" grade accreditation from the [[National Board of Accreditation]] (NBA) of India in 2003. The PGPM programme too is approved by [[AICTE]].<ref name=\"spjimr.org\"/> The [[Association of Indian Universities]] (AIU) recognises the two-year PGDM course as equivalent to an MBA degree of an Indian university.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.aiuweb.org/Evaluation/evaluation.asp | title = Name of the Institutions whose Postgraduate Diploma in Management has been equated with MBA Degree | publisher = Association of Indian Universities (AIU) | accessdate = 4 January 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n\nSPJIMR has a 7,000+ strong alumni network, which is also addressed as SPAN (SPJIMR Alumni Network). SPJIMR alumni include:\n\n;Business\n* [[Rajesh Jejurikar]], President and Chief Executive - Farm Equipment & Two Wheelers, [[Mahindra & Mahindra|Mahindra & Mahindra Ltd]] <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=184386583&privcapId=878402|title=Executive Profile Rajesh Ganesh Jejurikar|publisher=Bloomberg.com|accessdate=2016-05-20}}</ref>\n* [[Madan Padaki]], Co-founder and Director of Sylvant Advisors <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/sylvant-advisors-to-help-8-education-startups-raise-6-mn-115052101281_1.html|title=Sylvant to help 8 education startups raise $6 mn|publisher=Yourstory.com|date=2015-05-21|accessdate=2016-05-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://siteresources.worldbank.org/EDUCATION/Resources/278200-1121703274255/1439264-1260815500553/6646158-1261168095500/Madan_Padaki.pdf|title=South-South Learning Visit Feb 8-21 India|publisher=Siteresources.worldbank.org|accessdate=2016-05-20}}</ref>\n* [[Sunil Lulla]], Chairman and MD of [[Grey Global Group|Grey Group]], India <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/companies/sunil-lulla-appointed-cmd-for-grey-group-india/article6176817.ece|title=Sunil Lulla appointed CMD for Grey Group India|publisher=Thehindubusinessline.com|date=2014-07-04|accessdate=2016-05-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=13445211&privcapId=39435789|title=Sunil Lulla profile|work=Bloomberg Businessweek|accessdate=2016-05-20}}</ref>\n* [[Girish Wagh]], Head, Commercial vehicle business unit [[Tata Motors]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2008-01-12/news/27735671_1_small-car-tata-nano-car-project|title=Designer Girish Wagh: The whizkid who shaped Tata Nano|publisher=Economictimes.com|date=2008-01-12|accessdate=2016-05-20}}</ref>\n* [[Shiju Radhakrishnan]], Founder and CEO of iTraveller.com <ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2015-08-23/news/65769780_1_letsventure-iit-d-rs-32-lakh/3|title=How IIT alumni are turning funders and founders to create their own unique startup ecosystem|publisher=Economictimes.com|date=2015-08-23|accessdate=2016-05-19}}</ref>\n* [[Pradeep Kar]], Founder, Chairman and Managing Director of Microland <ref>{{cite web|url=http://archives.digitaltoday.in/businesstoday/20020331/features2.html|title=Tech Survivor|publisher=Digitaltoday.in|date=2002-03-31|accessdate=2016-05-20}}</ref>\n*[[Anant Bajaj]], MD, [[Bajaj Electricals]]\n\n;Arts\n* [[Siddharth (actor)|Siddharth Suryanarayan]], Indian film actor, Screenplay writer, Producer and Playback singer <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businesstoday.in/magazine/cover-story/what-they-dont-teach-you-at-bschool/story/4716.html|title=What they don't teach you at B-school|publisher=Businesstoday.in|date=2009-10-18|accessdate=2016-05-20}}</ref>\n\n;Sports\n* [[Dipankar Bhattacharjee]], Olympian and National Badmintion Champion, and Founder of Dipankar's Badminton Academy, Guwahati <ref>{{cite web|url=http://olympiandipankar.com/coach|title=Dipankar's Badminton Academy|publisher=olympiandipankar.com|accessdate=2016-05-20}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|S. P. Jain Institute of Management and Research}}\n* {{official}} \n\n{{Mumbai topics|state=collapsed}}  \n\n[[Category:Jain universities and colleges]]\n[[Category:Business schools in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges affiliated with the Bharatiya Vidya Bhavan]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1981]]\n[[Category:1981 establishments in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox university\n |name              = SP Jain Institute of Management and Research\n |image             = S. P. Jain Institute of Management and Research logo.svg\n |motto             = {{lang-sa|\u0905\u092e\u0943\u0924\u0902 \u0924\u0941 \u0935\u093f\u0926\u094d\u092f\u093e}}\n |mottoeng          = Knowledge is Nectar\n |established       = 1981\n |type              = [[Private school#India|Private]] [[business school]]\n |dean              = Ranjan Banerjee<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spjimr.org/newsroom/pressnotes/dr-ranjan-banner-takes-over-as-new-dean.asp|title=Press Notes - Dr.Ranjan Banerjee takes over as the Dean of SPJIMR|work=spjimr.org}}</ref>\n |students          = \n |city              = [[Mumbai]]\n |state             = [[Maharashtra]]\n |country           = [[India]]\n |campus            = [[Andheri]] (Urban area)\n |website           = [http://www.spjimr.org spjimr.org] \n |affiliations      = [[Association of Indian Universities|AIU]], [[Association of MBAs|AMBA]], [[AACSB]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/services/education/spjimr-earns-aacsb-international-accreditation/articleshow/66847736.cms|title=SPJIMR earns AACSB International Accreditation|last=|first=|date=28 Nov 2018|work=[[The Economic Times]]|access-date=9 Feb 2019|archive-url=https://archive.fo/n0ZVr|archive-date=9 Feb 2019|language=English}}</ref>\n }}\n'''S.P. Jain Institute of Management and Research''' ('''SPJIMR''') is a [[Private school#India|private]] [[business school]] affiliated under [[Bharatiya Vidya Bhavan]]. SPJIMR sits on a 45-acre campus in the western suburbs of [[Andheri]] in [[Mumbai]]. The Institute has an annual intake of approximately 700 students under various educational programmes with the [[Post Graduate Diploma in Management]] (PGDM) being the institution's oldest offered course.\n\n== History ==\n\nInaugurated in 1981 by the then British Prime Minister, [[Margaret Thatcher]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.margaretthatcher.org/document/104629|title= Speech by Margaret Thatcher at the inauguration|work=margaretthatcher.org}}</ref> SPJIMR had modest beginnings as a small extension of the campus of [[Bharatiya Vidya Bhavan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bhavans.info/|title=bhavans.info|work=bhavans.info}}</ref> The institute was named after [[Shreyans Prasad Jain|Sahu Shreyans Prasad Jain]] of the [[Sahu Jain]] family, who financed the institution in its early years. At the time of its establishment, SPJIMR was among the three business schools in Mumbai.<ref name=\"discover_spjim\">{{cite web|url=http://www.spjimr.org/discover_spjimr/discover_spjimr.asp|title=Discover SPJIMR - S P Jain Institute of Management & Research, Mumbai|work=spjimr.org}}</ref> After financing from the Sahu Jain family stopped, the institute disaffiliated itself from [[Bombay University]] to provide itself with more freedom in curriculum decision-making and pedagogy design.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spjimr.org/discover_spjimr/discover_spjimr.asp|title= Introduction|work=spjimr.org}}</ref> SPJIMR is a part of the Bharatiya Vidya Bhavan and operates out of its campus at Munshi Nagar, Dadabhai Road, Andheri West, Mumbai.\n\n== Academics ==\n{{copyedit section|for=Per [[WP:UNIGUIDE]], programmes should not be listed. This should be summarized as an \"Academics\" section.|date=February 2020}}\n[[File:SPJIMR classroom 2008.jpg|thumb|A lecture hall at SPJIMR]]\n\n===Post Graduate Diploma in Management===\nSPJIMR's Post Graduate Diploma in Management (PGDM)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spjimr.org/pgdm/program-overview.aspx|title=PGDM programme Overview - Post Graduate Diploma in Management Programme (PGDM) - Equivalent to 2 Year Full Time MBA - SPJIMR, Mumbai|work=spjimr.org}}</ref> is a two-year full-time residential programme equivalent to an MBA. The programme offers specializations in Finance, Operations, Marketing and Information Management. The programme has consistently been ranked among the top 10 in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bschools.businesstoday.in/?year=2014&college=SPJIMR-Mumbai&rank=5|title= 'India's Best Business Schools' by Business Today|work=businesstoday.in}}</ref> It is accredited by [[AICTE]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spjimr.org/discover_spjimr/accreditations_and_achievements.asp|title=SPJIMR - Accreditations and Achievements|work=spjimr.org}}</ref>\nThe programme has seen much pedagogical experimentation over the years, including social projects and business plans,<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.rediff.com/money/2006/jun/28mnc.htm | title = Fortune 500 co to support Mumbai slum | date = 28 June 2006| publisher = [[Rediff.com]] | accessdate = 4 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url =  http://www.financialexpress.com/news/social-projects-spjimr-alumni/72131/ |  title = Social Projects: SPJIMR Alumni | date = 23 December 2003 | publisher = [[The Financial Express (India)|The Financial Express]] | accessdate = 4 January 2010}}</ref> use of theatre to learn management,<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.telegraphindia.com/1071223/jsp/7days/story_8700287.jsp | title = All the B-world's a stage | publisher = [[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] | location = [[Calcutta]] | date = 23 December 2007 | accessdate = 4 January 2010 }}</ref> Assessment and Development of Managerial Potential (ADMAP, a programme where students participate in the administration of the college)<ref>{{cite news | title = Self-Reliance \u2013 SPJIMR Saga: S.P. Jain Institute of Management combines management studies with social responsibilities | publisher = India Business Insight | date = 8 June 2003 }}</ref> and India-specific [[case method|cases]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.business-standard.com/india/news/studying-sonia/242249/ | title = Studying Sonia | author = Kalpana Pathak | publisher = Business Standard | date = 6 April 2006 | accessdate = 4 January 2010}}</ref> SPJIMR does not have a traditional summer internship projects like most other Indian B-schools.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.expressindia.com/news/fe/daily/19990411/fle11079.html | title = Self-study at SPJIMR this season | author = Nivedita Mookerji | date = 11 April 1999 | accessdate = 4 January 2010 | publisher = [[The Indian Express]]}}</ref> Instead, the students are required to work with NGOs in the rural areas during the summer; corporate internships happen during autumn instead.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.financialexpress.com/printer/news/79268/ | title = Mumbai-based B-schools Go Beyond Summer Projects | date = 1 April 2003 | accessdate = 4 January 2004 | publisher = [[The Financial Express (India)|The Financial Express]]}}</ref>\n\n===Post Graduate Programme in Management===\nThe Post Graduate Programme in Management (PGPM), formerly known as Post Graduate Diploma in Management (PGDM), is a 15-month (3 months of foundation courses through web learning), full-time residential programme accredited by the [[Association of MBAs]].<ref name=\"pgpm_ad\">{{cite web|url=http://epaper.timesofindia.com/Default/Scripting/ArticleWin.asp?From=Archive&Source=Page&Skin=ETNEW&BaseHref=ETM/2009/06/08&PageLabel=3&ForceGif=true&EntityId=Ad00308&ViewMode=HTML&GZ=T|title=Article Window|work=timesofindia.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.telegraphindia.com/1060928/asp/careergraph/story_6800326.asp | title = Short haul MBA | date = 28 September 2006 | publisher = [[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] | location = [[Calcutta]] | accessdate = 4 January 2010}}</ref> and AICTE.<ref name=\"spjimr.org\">https://www.spjimr.org/pgpm/programme</ref> It offers specialisations in [[Marketing Management|Marketing]], Finance, [[Operations Management|Operations and Supply Chain]], and [[Information Management]]. The course includes a stint at partner foreign universities such as [[Cornell University]], Michigan State University and Texas University as part of the specialization phase. The specializations are chosen at the time of admission. The program admits working professionals with a minimum of 5 years of professional experience from domains and leading industries to enable knowledge sharing and peer learning.  The course starts in January and ends in December.\n\n===Global Management Programme===\nThe Global Management Programme (GMP) which was previously called the Post Graduate Certificate in International Management (PGCIM) is a full-time residential MBA program with an international focus. As a part of this program, students complete the first 8 months of their studies in SPJIMR, Mumbai and then complete their international stint at a partner university. This program was started by the Center of Indo European Business Studies(CIEBS) which was funded by the European Union.<ref name=\"pgcim\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ciebs.de/|title=Startseite - CIEBS: Centre for Indio-European Business Studies|author=ESB Business School Reutlingen University|date=5 February 2015|work=ciebs.de}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"pgcim_overview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.spjimr.org/pgcim/pgcim-overview.aspx|title=International MBA Program from Top Business Schools at SPJIMR, Mumbai India|work=spjimr.org}}</ref> The MBA program requires a minimum of 3 years of work experience; students with prior international exposure are preferred.\n\n===Executive Management Programme===\nThe Executive Management Programme (EMP) is a non-residential programme, for working professionals, similar to an [[Master of Business Administration|EMBA]], with 60 full-day classes on campus, spread over 21 months and contact sessions. The programme considers graduates with minimum five years of experience, and mandates the support of the candidate's company.<ref name=\"spjimr_emp\">[http://www.spjimr.org/emba/emba_home.asp EMBA Home] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080930030707/http://www.spjimr.org/emba/emba_home.asp |date=30 September 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===Family Managed Business programme===\nThe Family Managed Business (FMB) program is designed for candidates to lead their [[family business]]es. The duration of the program is two years and includes a foreign visit. The participants spent a week at the institute to learn and the remaining three weeks of the month at their workplace. The duration of the Owner Manager Programme is twelve months. Selection requires sponsorship from the business, a test, and a personal interview. The degree awarded is a Post Graduate Programme in Management.<ref>http://spjimr.org/sites/default/files/AICTE%20Approval%20-%202017-2018.pdf\n\nhttps://insideiim.com/spjimr-launch-of-fellow-programme-in-management/\n\nhttp://businessworld.in/article/SPJIMR-Imparting-360-Degree-Education/11-11-2016-108121/\n\nhttps://www.flipsnack.com/SPJIMR/spjimr-news-sep-16.html?b=1&p=50\n</ref>\n\n'''Post Graduate Management Programme in Development Management (PGPDM)'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://spjimr.org/pgpdm|title=Academic Why PGPDM {{!}} SPJIMR|website=spjimr.org|language=en|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref> \n\nIn SPJIMR\u2019s endeavour to enable \u201cfor-profit\u201d business management practices in the exponentially growing 'not-for-profit' sector, '''[https://spjimr.org/cedss CEdSS]''' offers '''PGPDM -''' A specialized executive management programme, for professionals working in the Social Development Sector including '''NGOs''', '''Corporate- CSRs''', '''Social Enterprises''' and people who do career transition. It is an 18 months modular program where participants come on campus for 6-8 days every 2 months, for the remaining 7 weeks they apply the learning to their organizational setting and undertake distant learning. PGDM is accredited by AMBA, one of the top three UK based global accreditation bodies which denote the highest standard of achievement in postgraduate business education as a unique program globally.\n\n'''Post Graduate Management Programme for Women (PGMPW)''' In 2016, SPJIMR launched the Post Graduate Management Programme for Women (PGMPW), targeted especially at women who have taken a break of more than two years after working in business roles. The 11-month full-time program seeks to prepare participants to return to a full-time career in senior managerial and leadership roles. \n<ref>http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/industry/services/education/sp-jain-institute-of-management-and-research-launches-management-programme-for-women/articleshow/53965438.cms\n\nhttp://www.ptinews.com/pressrelease/20175_press-subSPJIMR-Launches-a-Management-Programme-for-Women-Aspiring-to-Return-to-the-Workforce\n\nhttp://womanatwork.in/blog/sp-jain-institute-of-management-and-research-launches-management-programme-for-women/\n</ref>\n\n'''Fellow Programme in Management (FPM)'''\nSPJIMR launched a Fellow Programme in Management (FPM) in 2016 with an approved intake of five participants every year.  Participants of the FPM, which is a full-time doctoral-level program, undertake guided research in their chosen area of management studies after completing the prescribed coursework and are awarded as \u201cFellow of SPJIMR\u201d on successful completion of the program.<ref>http://spjimr.org/sites/default/files/AICTE%20Approval%20-%202017-2018.pdf\n\nhttps://insideiim.com/spjimr-launch-of-fellow-programme-in-management/\n\nhttp://businessworld.in/article/SPJIMR-Imparting-360-Degree-Education/11-11-2016-108121/ \nhttps://www.flipsnack.com/SPJIMR/spjimr-news-sep-16.html?b=1&p=50\n</ref>\n===Other programmes===\nSPJIMR offers several short term programs. Some of these are:  Start Your Business program (SYB) aimed at budding entrepreneurs, Grow Your Business program (GYB) to help meet the common challenges faced by small business owners and a program in Strategic Media & Entertainment Management (PSMEM) conducted in partnership with the Times Centre for Learning Ltd. (TCLL).<ref>http://www.prnewswire.co.in/news-releases/more-start-ups-led-by-spjimr-alumni-attract-funding-609871325.html</ref> SPJIMR runs several Management Development Programmes (MDPs), some of which are in areas like Leadership, Supply Chain Analytics, HR, IT Strategic Planning, Design Thinking and Analytics in Marketing. The PMP Certificate Preparatory program, the Advanced Project Management, and Agile Project Management programs are offered as part of Project Management group of programs.<ref>http://epaperbeta.timesofindia.com/Article.aspx?eid=31804&articlexml=Times-Group-launches-strategic-media-mgmt-course-with-17032017022034\n\n</ref>\n\n==Rankings==\n{{Infobox India university ranking\n|type=Institute\n| NIRF_B_2019 = 16\n| BT_2019 = 4\n| OUTLOOK_B_2018 = 6\n| QS_B_2019 = 201+\n| QS_B_A_2019 = 18\n}}\nGlobally, The ''[[Quacquarelli Symonds|QS]] Global 250 MBA Rankings 2019'' ranked SPJIMR 201+ in the world<ref name=Rankings_QS_B_2019/> and 18 in Asia.<ref name=Rankings_QS_B_A_2019/>\n\nIn India, SPJIMR was ranked 16 among management schools by the [[National Institutional Ranking Framework]] (NIRF) in 2019,<ref name=Rankings_NIRF_B_2019/> fourth by ''[[Business Today (India)|Business Today]]''{{'}}s \"India's best B-schools 2019\"<ref name=Rankings_BT_2019 /> and sixth in India by ''[[Outlook India]]''{{'}}s \"Top 100 Management Schools\" of 2018.<ref name=Rankings_OUTLOOK_B_2018 />\n\n== Lock, Stock & Trade ==\nLock, Stock & Trade is an annual national-level  mock investment game organised by SPJIMR in association with the [[National Entrepreneurship Network]] (NEN).<ref>[http://www.thehindubusinessline.in/bline/2005/09/28/stories/2005092802210800.htm S.P. Jain's new programme to groom students]. ''[[The Hindu]]''. 25 September 2008.</ref>\n\n== Accreditation ==\n\nThe [[Association of MBAs]] (AMBA) has accorded accreditation to SPJIMR's two-year PGDM, one-year PGPM and the Executive Management Programme (EMP).<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.mbaworld.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=474&Itemid=132 | title = Accredited MBA Programmes | publisher = AMBA | accessdate = 4 January 2010}}</ref> The PGDM programme is approved by [[AICTE]] and received \"A\" grade accreditation from the [[National Board of Accreditation]] (NBA) of India in 2003. The PGPM programme too is approved by [[AICTE]].<ref name=\"spjimr.org\"/> The [[Association of Indian Universities]] (AIU) recognises the two-year PGDM course as equivalent to an MBA degree of an Indian university.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.aiuweb.org/Evaluation/evaluation.asp | title = Name of the Institutions whose Postgraduate Diploma in Management has been equated with MBA Degree | publisher = Association of Indian Universities (AIU) | accessdate = 4 January 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n\nSPJIMR has a 7,000+ strong alumni network, which is also addressed as SPAN (SPJIMR Alumni Network). SPJIMR alumni include:\n\n;Business\n* [[Rajesh Jejurikar]], President and Chief Executive - Farm Equipment & Two Wheelers, [[Mahindra & Mahindra|Mahindra & Mahindra Ltd]] <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=184386583&privcapId=878402|title=Executive Profile Rajesh Ganesh Jejurikar|publisher=Bloomberg.com|accessdate=2016-05-20}}</ref>\n* [[Madan Padaki]], Co-founder and Director of Sylvant Advisors <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/sylvant-advisors-to-help-8-education-startups-raise-6-mn-115052101281_1.html|title=Sylvant to help 8 education startups raise $6 mn|publisher=Yourstory.com|date=2015-05-21|accessdate=2016-05-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://siteresources.worldbank.org/EDUCATION/Resources/278200-1121703274255/1439264-1260815500553/6646158-1261168095500/Madan_Padaki.pdf|title=South-South Learning Visit Feb 8-21 India|publisher=Siteresources.worldbank.org|accessdate=2016-05-20}}</ref>\n* [[Sunil Lulla]], Chairman and MD of [[Grey Global Group|Grey Group]], India <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/companies/sunil-lulla-appointed-cmd-for-grey-group-india/article6176817.ece|title=Sunil Lulla appointed CMD for Grey Group India|publisher=Thehindubusinessline.com|date=2014-07-04|accessdate=2016-05-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=13445211&privcapId=39435789|title=Sunil Lulla profile|work=Bloomberg Businessweek|accessdate=2016-05-20}}</ref>\n* [[Girish Wagh]], Head, Commercial vehicle business unit [[Tata Motors]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2008-01-12/news/27735671_1_small-car-tata-nano-car-project|title=Designer Girish Wagh: The whizkid who shaped Tata Nano|publisher=Economictimes.com|date=2008-01-12|accessdate=2016-05-20}}</ref>\n* [[Shiju Radhakrishnan]], Founder and CEO of iTraveller.com <ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2015-08-23/news/65769780_1_letsventure-iit-d-rs-32-lakh/3|title=How IIT alumni are turning funders and founders to create their own unique startup ecosystem|publisher=Economictimes.com|date=2015-08-23|accessdate=2016-05-19}}</ref>\n* [[Pradeep Kar]], Founder, Chairman and Managing Director of Microland <ref>{{cite web|url=http://archives.digitaltoday.in/businesstoday/20020331/features2.html|title=Tech Survivor|publisher=Digitaltoday.in|date=2002-03-31|accessdate=2016-05-20}}</ref>\n*[[Anant Bajaj]], MD, [[Bajaj Electricals]]\n\n;Arts\n* [[Siddharth (actor)|Siddharth Suryanarayan]], Indian film actor, Screenplay writer, Producer and Playback singer <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businesstoday.in/magazine/cover-story/what-they-dont-teach-you-at-bschool/story/4716.html|title=What they don't teach you at B-school|publisher=Businesstoday.in|date=2009-10-18|accessdate=2016-05-20}}</ref>\n\n;Sports\n* [[Dipankar Bhattacharjee]], Olympian and National Badmintion Champion, and Founder of Dipankar's Badminton Academy, Guwahati <ref>{{cite web|url=http://olympiandipankar.com/coach|title=Dipankar's Badminton Academy|publisher=olympiandipankar.com|accessdate=2016-05-20}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|S. P. Jain Institute of Management and Research}}\n* {{official}} \n\n{{Mumbai topics|state=collapsed}}  \n\n[[Category:Jain universities and colleges]]\n[[Category:Business schools in Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges affiliated with the Bharatiya Vidya Bhavan]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1981]]\n[[Category:1981 establishments in India]]\n", "name_user": "Harinath Krishnamurthy", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S._P._Jain_Institute_of_Management_and_Research"}
{"title_page": "Making Mirrors", "text_new": "{{short description|Album by Gotye}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=December 2011}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Making Mirrors\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Gotye]]\n| cover      = Gotye - Making Mirrors.png\n| border     = yes\n| alt        =\n| released   = 19 August 2011\n| recorded   = 2008\u201311\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Indie rock]]\n*[[art pop]]\n*[[indie pop]]\n*[[art rock]]\n}}\n| length     = 42:21\n| label      = [[Eleven: A Music Company|Eleven]]\n| producer   = Wally De Backer\n| prev_title = [[Mixed Blood (album)|Mixed Blood]]\n| prev_year  = 2007\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Making Mirrors\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Eyes Wide Open (Gotye song)|Eyes Wide Open]]\n | single1date = 5 November 2010\n | single2     = [[Somebody That I Used to Know]]\n | single2date = 5 July 2011\n | single3     = Bronte\n | single3date = 8 August 2011\n | single4     = [[I Feel Better (Gotye song)|I Feel Better]]\n | single4date = 24 October 2011\n | single5     = Easy Way Out\n | single5date = 27 February 2012\n | single6     = [[Save Me (Gotye song)|Save Me]]\n | single6date = 13 August 2012\n | single7     = State of the Art\n | single7date = 2013\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Making Mirrors''''' is the third studio album by Belgian-Australian artist [[Gotye]]. The album was released in Australia on 19 August 2011. In December 2011 it was announced that ''Making Mirrors'' was voted [[Triple J]] listeners' number-one album of 2011, making Gotye the first artist to win the Triple J album poll twice. It included the hit \"[[Somebody That I Used to Know]]\", which reached and topped charts worldwide. In Poland, after one day of release, the album was certified platinum.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.polskieradio.pl/6/1020/Artykul/533962,Gotye-pokryl-sie-w-Polsce-platyna-w-jeden-dzien | title=Gotye pokry\u0142 si\u0119 w Polsce platyn\u0105 w jeden dzie\u0144! | publisher=polskieradio.pl | work=[[Polskie Radio]] | accessdate=5 March 2012}}</ref> The album won the [[2013 Grammy Awards|2013 Grammy]] for [[Best Alternative Music Album]].\n\nThe album was largely recorded at a converted studio at Gotye's parents' farm in the [[Mornington Peninsula]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Smirke|first=Richard|title=Gotye's Smash Hit Almost Didn't Happen|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/495278/gotyes-smash-hit-almost-didnt-happen|work=Billboard|accessdate=14 April 2012|date=13 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{Quote box\n| quote  = \"Eyes Wide Open\" saw Gotye explore new musical territory, with the main bass line from the song recorded on a fence: \"I was out there with my old band called The Basics\u2014and Winton is home to this phenomenal thing called the ''Winton Musical Fence'', which is a large fence made out of metal strings stretched between posts and you can pluck it and play it with all sorts of different materials - it makes these amazing bass sounds so I sampled some bits there in 08 and they made it into the first single I put out off the new record called ''Eyes Wide Open.''\"\n:\u2014Gotye.<ref name=\"abc.net.au\">{{cite web|last=Shorthouse |first=Janel |url=http://www.abc.net.au/local/stories/2011/07/28/3280357.htm |title=Gotye @ Splendour in the Grass - ABC Sunshine & Cooloola Coasts Qld - Australian Broadcasting Corporation |publisher=Abc.net.au |date=2011-07-28 |accessdate=2012-02-10}}</ref>\n| width  = 20em\n| align  = left\n| quoted = 1\n}}In mid-October 2010, Gotye released a single titled \"[[Eyes Wide Open (Gotye song)|Eyes Wide Open]]\", the first track from the album. The single received generally positive reviews and reached #25 in the [[Triple J]] [[Triple J Hottest 100|Hottest 100]] of [[Triple J Hottest 100, 2010|2010]].<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news|url=http://www.bendigoadvertiser.com.au/news/local/news/general/gotyes-mirrored-vision/2116370.aspx?storypage= |title=Gotye's Mirrored Vision |newspaper=Bendigo Advertiser |accessdate=29 March 2011}}</ref> In late March 2010, Gotye revealed the album's title, which was inspired by an artwork De Backer chanced upon which was edited to create the album cover art. He claimed, \"The mirror reflects on artwork and it is all very related to self-reflection and introspection on the album.\"<ref name=autogenerated1 /> Gotye also revealed that the album would see a release in June or July 2011, with a single to precede the release,<ref name=autogenerated1 /> along with the fact that the album would be similar to its predecessor in terms of diversity.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> Gotye went on to reveal that the release of the album was delayed for over five months due to the composition and recording of a single track.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gotye.com/news.html|title=News|work=Gotye|access-date=25 June 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110924082621/http://gotye.com/news.html|archive-date=24 September 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 May 2011, it was announced that this album would be released on 19 August 2011, with the album to be launched the following day at the [[Sydney Opera House]] as part of the Graphic Festival, with animators and a ten-piece orchestra as part of Gotye's performance.<ref name=\"undercover.fm\">{{cite web|url=http://www.undercover.fm/news/14797-gotye-debuts-new-album-at-the-opera-house |title=Gotye Debuts New Album At The Opera House - Undercover.fm News |publisher=Undercover.fm |date=18 May 2011 |accessdate=10 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110907015200/http://www.undercover.fm/news/14797-gotye-debuts-new-album-at-the-opera-house |archivedate=7 September 2011 }}</ref> Gotye was also to issue a follow-up single to \"Eyes Wide Open\" titled \"Somebody That I Used to Know\", on 11 July 2011.<ref name=\"undercover.fm\"/> Upon the announcement of the track listing, Gotye also revealed that there would be a DVD accompanying the record which would include music videos and documentaries.<ref name=\"gotye.com\">{{cite web|url=http://gotye.com/|title=Home|work=Gotye|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111222113644/http://gotye.com/|archivedate=22 December 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> However, controversy erupted on 5 July 2011, when the video for the new single, \"Somebody That I Used to Know\", was leaked online via the [[Austereo Radio Network]]'s [[Take 40 Australia|Take 40]] website. Later that day, the song was aired for the first time on [[Triple J]] with the official stamp of approval from Gotye.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.twitter.com/gotye |title=Twitter |publisher=Twitter |date= |accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref> Gotye released the single six days early, on 5 July 2011, through [[iTunes Store|iTunes]] Australia, and his website for international followers.\n\nThe song has also reached #1 in the ARIA Singles Chart,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/pages/charts_display_singles.asp?chart=1U50 |title=Top 50 Singles Chart - Australian Record Industry Association |publisher=Ariacharts.com.au |accessdate=10 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100208082123/http://www.ariacharts.com.au/pages/charts_display_singles.asp?chart=1U50 |archivedate=8 February 2010 }}</ref> and the ARIA Digital Singles Chart<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/pages/charts_display_digital.asp?chart=1DT40 |title=Top 40 Digital Track Chart - Australian Record Industry Association |publisher=Ariacharts.com.au |accessdate=10 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100917073232/http://ariacharts.com.au/pages/charts_display_digital.asp?chart=1DT40 |archivedate=17 September 2010 }}</ref> and #1 in the ARIA Australian Artists Chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/pages/charts_display_australian.asp?chart=1U20AUS&chart2=1G20AUS |title=Top 20 Australian Singles & Albums Chart - Australian Record Industry Association |publisher=Ariacharts.com.au |accessdate=10 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106051658/http://www.ariacharts.com.au/pages/charts_display_australian.asp?chart=1U20AUS&chart2=1G20AUS |archivedate=6 January 2012 }}</ref> The song went on to be an international success charting in the top 20 in over 10 countries with 6 of them being at number one; the song also charted in the US and Canada. As of Friday 4 November, the single has received five times platinum sales and the #1 position on the Australian [[iTunes Store]], making it one of the highest-selling singles of 2011. The single has officially been certified nine times platinum, selling over 630,000 copies, making it the most successful Australian song on the ARIA charts of all time. The album was certified two times platinum by the ARIA Albums Chart, making it the most successful Australian album of 2011. Since then, the album has been certified three times platinum, selling in excess of 210,000 copies in Australia. \"Bronte\" was released as the third single on 8 August 2011. \"[[I Feel Better (Gotye song)|I Feel Better]]\" was released as the fourth single from the album in Australia on 24 October 2011.<ref name=\"musicnetwork\">{{cite web|url=http://www.themusicnetwork.com/music-releases/singles/2011/10/24/issue--859/gotye---i-feel-better/|title=GOTYE \u2013 I Feel Better \u2013 Issue 859|work=The Music Network|publisher=Peer Media Group|accessdate=3 February 2011}}</ref> The song, however, failed to reach the top 100. \"Easy Way Out\" was released in the UK as a promotional single on 3 November 2011. It was eventually released as the fifth single from Making Mirrors in Australia on 27 February 2012.\n\n==Concept and themes==\nShortly before its release, Gotye spoke to the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]] about the significance of the artwork, the title, and how it symbolises the creative and introspective process of recording the album; \"It's more about reflection - the look at yourself that a mirror offers and also the way it gives you a different perspective on things around you. So I guess I feel a bit analogous to what these songs become to me\u2014you know little ways for me to explore my record collection, explore the world of sound that I'm fascinated by, and also sometimes get a different perspective on memories and emotions I've been mulling over that they find voice in these songs\".<ref name=\"abc.net.au\"/>\n\nGotye revealed that the second single from the album, \"Somebody That I Used to Know\", was not lyrically the result of a single break-up. \"It wasn't about one specific relationship,\" explained De Backer in an interview, \"but it was definitely drawn from various experiences I've had in relationships breaking up, and in the parts of the more reflective parts of the song, in the aftermath and the memory of those different relationships and what they were and how they broke up and what's going on in everyone's minds. Yeah, so it's an amalgam of different feelings but not completely made up as such.\"<ref name=\"abc.net.au\"/>\n\nDespite the album's huge success, Gotye revealed in an interview with ''[[Rolling Stone Australia]]'' that he initially battled with indecision and depression while making the album, which in turn became the subject matter of songs like \"Smoke and Mirrors\" (with a central theme of [[impostor syndrome]]) and \"Save Me\". He stated: \"There were points that I thought I wouldn't be able to finish a record I was really into or that I'd give up at some stage.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Treuen |first=Jason |url=http://jasontreuen.wordpress.com/2011/10/30/rolling-stone-gotyes-mad-world/ |title=Rolling Stone: Gotye's Mad World |work=[[Rolling Stone Australia]] |date=30 October 2011 |accessdate=30 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nAccording to an interview in ''The Age'', the track \"State of the Art\" is about a secondhand 1970s organ Gotye's parents purchased. The accompanying music video is an animation showing a family purchasing and playing the instrument.\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| ADM = 6.6/10<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/review/3590/Gotye-Making-Mirrors.aspx |title=Making Mirrors by Gotye reviews |publisher=[[AnyDecentMusic?]] |accessdate=28 December 2019}}</ref>\n| MC = 69/100<ref name=\"MC\"/>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |last=O'Brien |first=Jon |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/making-mirrors-mw0002204056 |title=Making Mirrors \u2013 Gotye |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=3 June 2012}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Patrick |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/cdreviews/9071618/Gotye-Making-Mirrors-CD-review.html |title=Gotye: Making Mirrors, CD review |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=9 February 2012 |accessdate=3 June 2012 |location=London}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev3Score = B+<ref>{{cite web |last1=Anderson |first1=Kyle |last2=Rahman |first2=Ray |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2012/01/27/albums-feb-3-2012 |title=Albums: Feb. 3, 2012 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=27 January 2012 |accessdate=19 April 2012}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite news |last=Sullivan |first=Caroline |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/feb/09/gotye-making-mirrors-review |title=Gotye: Making Mirrors \u2013 review |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=9 February 2012 |accessdate=3 June 2012 |location=London}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[The Independent]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite news |last=Gill |first=Andy |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-gotye-making-mirrors-island-6699391.html |title=Album: Gotye, Making Mirrors (Island) |work=[[The Independent]] |date=10 February 2012 |accessdate=19 April 2012 |location=London |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120910154833/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-gotye-making-mirrors-island-6699391.html |archivedate=10 September 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev6Score = 5/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Malone |first=Ailbhe |url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/gotye/12711 |title=Gotye \u2013 'Making Mirrors' |work=[[NME]] |date=10 February 2012 |accessdate=19 April 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305070624/http://www.nme.com/reviews/gotye/12711 |archivedate=5 March 2016}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev7Score = 7.7/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Love |first=Joshua |url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/15749-making-mirrors/ |title=Gotye: Making Mirrors |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=9 September 2011 |accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |title=Gotye: Making Mirrors |work=[[Q (magazine)|Q]] |issue=309 |date=April 2012 |page=107}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev9Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |last=Rosen |first=Jody |authorlink=Jody Rosen |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/making-mirrors-20120214 |title=Making Mirrors |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=14 February 2012 |accessdate=19 April 2012}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]''\n| rev10Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |title=Gotye: Making Mirrors |work=[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]] |issue=178 |date=March 2012 |page=87}}</ref>\n}}\n''Making Mirrors'' received generally positive reviews from music critics. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[standard score|normalised]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the album received an [[weighted mean|average]] score of 69, based on 19 reviews, which indicates \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/making-mirrors |title=Reviews for Making Mirrors by Gotye |publisher=[[Metacritic]]. [[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=3 June 2012}}</ref> Caitlin Welsh of ''[[The Music Network]]'' gave the album a favourable review, saying that it was \"just as rich, cheeky and steeped in pop history and musicality as its predecessor and as {{Sic|hide=y|carefully|-}}constructed and addictive as its breakout track ('[[Somebody That I Used to Know]]'), it will cement Wally de Backer as the oddball, everyman genius of Australian pop.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Welsh |first=Caitlin |url=http://www.themusicnetwork.com/reviews/album/2011/08/19/Gotye-Making-Mirrors/ |title=Album Review: Gotye, Making Mirrors |work=The Music Network |publisher=Peer Group Media |date=19 August 2011}}</ref> ''The Herald Sun'' gave it four out of five stars, adding that \"''Bronte'' and ''Giving Me a Chance'' are the latest in a long line of beautiful, visual songs begging to soundtrack the pivotal scene in a movie that's yet to be made.\"<ref name=\"heraldsun.com.au\">{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/music/album-review-making-mirrors-by-gotye-elevenuniversal/story-fn7oonq8-1226117613340 |title=Album review: Making Mirrors by Gotye (Eleven/Universal) |newspaper=Herald Sun |date=18 August 2011 |accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref> Radar Radio also gave ''Making Mirrors'' four out of five stars and regarding the track \"Eyes Wide Open\" said, \"with lyrics like 'Some people offered up answers / We made out like we heard / but they were only words / They didn't add up to a change in the way we were living'. Now don't get me wrong, I have never been in a situation like this yet it feels so relatable.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radarradio.com.au/artists/reviews/gotye-making-mirrors-review.aspx |title=Gotye Making Mirrors Review &#124; Radar Artists. Band info, interviews, reviews & artist music upload |publisher=Radar Radio |accessdate=10 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007080854/http://www.radarradio.com.au/artists/reviews/gotye-making-mirrors-review.aspx |archivedate=7 October 2011 }}</ref> The album won the 2013 [[Grammy Award]] for [[Best Alternative Music Album]].\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = [[Gotye|Wally De Backer]]\n| title1   = Making Mirrors\n| length1  = 1:01\n| title2   = Easy Way Out\n| length2  = 1:57\n| title3   = [[Somebody That I Used to Know]]\n| note3    = featuring [[Kimbra]]\n| length3  = 4:04\n| title4   = [[Eyes Wide Open (Gotye song)|Eyes Wide Open]]\n| length4  = 3:11\n| title5   = Smoke and Mirrors\n| length5  = 5:13\n| title6   = [[I Feel Better (Gotye song)|I Feel Better]]\n| length6  = 3:18\n| title7   = In Your Light\n| length7  = 4:39\n| title8   = State of the Art\n| length8  = 5:22\n| title9   = Don't Worry, We'll Be Watching You\n| length9  = 3:18\n| title10  = Giving Me a Chance\n| length10 = 3:07\n| title11  = [[Save Me (Gotye song)|Save Me]]\n| length11 = 3:53\n| title12  = Bronte\n| length12 = 3:18\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Digital-only tracks\n| title13  = Dig Your Own Hole\n| length13 = 4:23\n| title14  = Showdown Below My Sombrero\n| length14 = 2:30\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Limited edition bonus DVD\n| title1   = The Making of Eyes Wide Open\n| note1    = documentary\n| length1  = 8:01\n| title2   = Making ''Making Mirrors''\n| note2    = documentary\n| length2  = 10:03\n| title3   = Eyes Wide Open\n| note3    = music video<!--They are called MUSIC VIDEOS, not 'film clips'. That's an unofficial title and is inconsistent with Wikipedia-wide terming-->\n| length3  = 3:18\n| title4   = Somebody That I Used to Know\n| note4    = featuring Kimbra) (music video\n| length4  = 4:03\n| title5   = State of the Art\n| note5    = music video\n| length5  = 5:18\n| title6   = Bronte\n| note6    = music video\n| length6  = 3:14\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n*Wally De Backer \u2013 lead and backing vocals, songwriter, samples, instruments\n*Francois Tetaz \u2013 dubs and spaces on \"Making Mirrors\"\n*Lucas Taranto \u2013 bass guitar on \"Easy Way Out\", \"Somebody That I Used to Know\", \"I Feel Better\", \"Save Me\", poker bass on \"Eyes Wide Open\", fretless bass on \"Bronte\"\n*Kimbra \u2013 lead and backing vocals on \"Somebody That I Used to Know\"\n*Gareth Skinner \u2013 whale cellos on \"Eyes Wide Open\"\n*Michael Hubbard \u2013 [[pedal steel guitar]] on \"Eyes Wide Open\"\n*Luke Hodgson \u2013 bass guitar on \"I Feel Better\"\n*Scott Tinkler \u2013 trumpet on \"In Your Light\"\n*Adam Simmons \u2013 saxophone on \"In Your Light\"\n*Frank De Backer \u2013 album artwork\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (2011\u201312)\n!scope=\"col\"|Peak<br>position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[ARIA Charts|Australian Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Gotye&titel=Making+Mirrors&cat=a |title=Gotye \u2013 Making Mirrors |publisher=australian-charts.com. Hung Medien |accessdate=20 September 2011}}</ref>\n|1\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[\u00d63 Austria Top 40|Austrian Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://austriancharts.at/showitem.asp?interpret=Gotye&titel=Making+Mirrors&cat=a |title=Gotye \u2013 Making Mirrors |publisher=austriancharts.at. Hung Medien |accessdate=12 January 2012}}</ref>\n|6\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[Ultratop|Belgian Albums Chart]] (Flanders)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ultratop.be/nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Gotye&titel=Making+Mirrors&cat=a |title=Gotye \u2013 Making Mirrors |language=Dutch |publisher=[[Ultratop]]. Hung Medien |accessdate=20 September 2011}}</ref>\n|3\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[Ultratop|Belgian Albums Chart]] (Wallonia)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ultratop.be/fr/showitem.asp?interpret=Gotye&titel=Making+Mirrors&cat=a |title=Gotye \u2013 Making Mirrors |language=French |publisher=Ultratop. Hung Medien |accessdate=23 September 2011}}</ref>\n|6\n|-\n!sco