ing Mirrors]'' at [[Metacritic]]\n* {{YouTube|2ZXLyeatI0s|Making ''Making Mirrors'' \u2013 a short documentary}}\n\n{{Gotye}}\n{{ARIA Award for Album of the Year 2010s}}\n\n[[Category:2011 albums]]\n[[Category:ARIA Award-winning albums]]\n[[Category:Eleven: A Music Company albums]]\n[[Category:Gotye albums]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award for Best Alternative Music Album]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Album by Gotye}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=December 2011}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Making Mirrors\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Gotye]]\n| cover      = Gotye - Making Mirrors.png\n| border     = yes\n| alt        =\n| released   = 19 August 2011\n| recorded   = 2008\u201311\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Indie rock]]\n*[[art pop]]\n*[[indie pop]]\n*[[art rock]]\n}}\n| length     = 42:21\n| label      = [[Eleven: A Music Company|Eleven]]\n| producer   = Wally De Backer\n| prev_title = [[Mixed Blood (album)|Mixed Blood]]\n| prev_year  = 2007\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Making Mirrors\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Eyes Wide Open (Gotye song)|Eyes Wide Open]]\n | single1date = 5 November 2010\n | single2     = [[Somebody That I Used to Know]]\n | single2date = 5 July 2011\n | single3     = Bronte\n | single3date = 8 August 2011\n | single4     = [[I Feel Better (Gotye song)|I Feel Better]]\n | single4date = 24 October 2011\n | single5     = Easy Way Out\n | single5date = 27 February 2012\n | single6     = [[Save Me (Gotye song)|Save Me]]\n | single6date = 13 August 2012\n | single7     = State of the Art\n | single7date = 2013\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Making Mirrors''''' is the third studio album by Belgian-Australian artist [[Gotye]]. The album was released in Australia on 19 August 2011. In December 2011 it was announced that ''Making Mirrors'' was voted [[Triple J]] listeners' number-one album of 2011, making Gotye the first artist to win the Triple J album poll twice. It included the hit \"[[Somebody That I Used to Know]]\", which reached and topped charts worldwide. In Poland, after one day of release, the album was certified platinum.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.polskieradio.pl/6/1020/Artykul/533962,Gotye-pokryl-sie-w-Polsce-platyna-w-jeden-dzien | title=Gotye pokry\u0142 si\u0119 w Polsce platyn\u0105 w jeden dzie\u0144! | publisher=polskieradio.pl | work=[[Polskie Radio]] | accessdate=5 March 2012}}</ref> The album won the [[2013 Grammy Awards|2013 Grammy]] for [[Best Alternative Music Album]].\n\nThe album was largely recorded at a converted studio at Gotye's parents' farm in the [[Mornington Peninsula]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Smirke|first=Richard|title=Gotye's Smash Hit Almost Didn't Happen|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/495278/gotyes-smash-hit-almost-didnt-happen|work=Billboard|accessdate=14 April 2012|date=13 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{Quote box\n| quote  = \"Eyes Wide Open\" saw Gotye explore new musical territory, with the main bass line from the song recorded on a fence: \"I was out there with my old band called The Basics\u2014and Winton is home to this phenomenal thing called the ''Winton Musical Fence'', which is a large fence made out of metal strings stretched between posts and you can pluck it and play it with all sorts of different materials - it makes these amazing bass sounds so I sampled some bits there in 08 and they made it into the first single I put out off the new record called ''Eyes Wide Open.''\"\n:\u2014Gotye.<ref name=\"abc.net.au\">{{cite web|last=Shorthouse |first=Janel |url=http://www.abc.net.au/local/stories/2011/07/28/3280357.htm |title=Gotye @ Splendour in the Grass - ABC Sunshine & Cooloola Coasts Qld - Australian Broadcasting Corporation |publisher=Abc.net.au |date=2011-07-28 |accessdate=2012-02-10}}</ref>\n| width  = 20em\n| align  = left\n| quoted = 1\n}}In mid-October 2010, Gotye released a single titled \"[[Eyes Wide Open (Gotye song)|Eyes Wide Open]]\", the first track from the album. The single received generally positive reviews and reached #25 in the [[Triple J]] [[Triple J Hottest 100|Hottest 100]] of [[Triple J Hottest 100, 2010|2010]].<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news|url=http://www.bendigoadvertiser.com.au/news/local/news/general/gotyes-mirrored-vision/2116370.aspx?storypage= |title=Gotye's Mirrored Vision |newspaper=Bendigo Advertiser |accessdate=29 March 2011}}</ref> In late March 2010, Gotye revealed the album's title, which was inspired by an artwork De Backer chanced upon which was edited to create the album cover art. He claimed, \"The mirror reflects on artwork and it is all very related to self-reflection and introspection on the album.\"<ref name=autogenerated1 /> Gotye also revealed that the album would see a release in June or July 2011, with a single to precede the release,<ref name=autogenerated1 /> along with the fact that the album would be similar to its predecessor in terms of diversity.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> Gotye went on to reveal that the release of the album was delayed for over five months due to the composition and recording of a single track.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gotye.com/news.html|title=News|work=Gotye|access-date=25 June 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110924082621/http://gotye.com/news.html|archive-date=24 September 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 May 2011, it was announced that this album would be released on 19 August 2011, with the album to be launched the following day at the [[Sydney Opera House]] as part of the Graphic Festival, with animators and a ten-piece orchestra as part of Gotye's performance.<ref name=\"undercover.fm\">{{cite web|url=http://www.undercover.fm/news/14797-gotye-debuts-new-album-at-the-opera-house |title=Gotye Debuts New Album At The Opera House - Undercover.fm News |publisher=Undercover.fm |date=18 May 2011 |accessdate=10 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110907015200/http://www.undercover.fm/news/14797-gotye-debuts-new-album-at-the-opera-house |archivedate=7 September 2011 }}</ref> Gotye was also to issue a follow-up single to \"Eyes Wide Open\" titled \"Somebody That I Used to Know\", on 11 July 2011.<ref name=\"undercover.fm\"/> Upon the announcement of the track listing, Gotye also revealed that there would be a DVD accompanying the record which would include music videos and documentaries.<ref name=\"gotye.com\">{{cite web|url=http://gotye.com/|title=Home|work=Gotye|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111222113644/http://gotye.com/|archivedate=22 December 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> However, controversy erupted on 5 July 2011, when the video for the new single, \"Somebody That I Used to Know\", was leaked online via the [[Austereo Radio Network]]'s [[Take 40 Australia|Take 40]] website. Later that day, the song was aired for the first time on [[Triple J]] with the official stamp of approval from Gotye.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.twitter.com/gotye |title=Twitter |publisher=Twitter |date= |accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref> Gotye released the single six days early, on 5 July 2011, through [[iTunes Store|iTunes]] Australia, and his website for international followers.\n\nThe song has also reached #1 in the ARIA Singles Chart,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/pages/charts_display_singles.asp?chart=1U50 |title=Top 50 Singles Chart - Australian Record Industry Association |publisher=Ariacharts.com.au |accessdate=10 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100208082123/http://www.ariacharts.com.au/pages/charts_display_singles.asp?chart=1U50 |archivedate=8 February 2010 }}</ref> and the ARIA Digital Singles Chart<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/pages/charts_display_digital.asp?chart=1DT40 |title=Top 40 Digital Track Chart - Australian Record Industry Association |publisher=Ariacharts.com.au |accessdate=10 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100917073232/http://ariacharts.com.au/pages/charts_display_digital.asp?chart=1DT40 |archivedate=17 September 2010 }}</ref> and #1 in the ARIA Australian Artists Chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/pages/charts_display_australian.asp?chart=1U20AUS&chart2=1G20AUS |title=Top 20 Australian Singles & Albums Chart - Australian Record Industry Association |publisher=Ariacharts.com.au |accessdate=10 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106051658/http://www.ariacharts.com.au/pages/charts_display_australian.asp?chart=1U20AUS&chart2=1G20AUS |archivedate=6 January 2012 }}</ref> The song went on to be an international success charting in the top 20 in over 10 countries with 6 of them being at number one; the song also charted in the US and Canada. As of Friday 4 November, the single has received five times platinum sales and the #1 position on the Australian [[iTunes Store]], making it one of the highest-selling singles of 2011. The single has officially been certified nine times platinum, selling over 630,000 copies, making it the most successful Australian song on the ARIA charts of all time. The album was certified two times platinum by the ARIA Albums Chart, making it the most successful Australian album of 2011. Since then, the album has been certified three times platinum, selling in excess of 210,000 copies in Australia. \"Bronte\" was released as the third single on 8 August 2011. \"[[I Feel Better (Gotye song)|I Feel Better]]\" was released as the fourth single from the album in Australia on 24 October 2011.<ref name=\"musicnetwork\">{{cite web|url=http://www.themusicnetwork.com/music-releases/singles/2011/10/24/issue--859/gotye---i-feel-better/|title=GOTYE \u2013 I Feel Better \u2013 Issue 859|work=The Music Network|publisher=Peer Media Group|accessdate=3 February 2011}}</ref> The song, however, failed to reach the top 100. \"Easy Way Out\" was released in the UK as a promotional single on 3 November 2011. It was eventually released as the fifth single from Making Mirrors in Australia on 27 February 2012.\n\n==Concept and themes==\nShortly before its release, Gotye spoke to the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]] about the significance of the artwork, the title, and how it symbolises the creative and introspective process of recording the album; \"It's more about reflection - the look at yourself that a mirror offers and also the way it gives you a different perspective on things around you. So I guess I feel a bit analogous to what these songs become to me\u2014you know little ways for me to explore my record collection, explore the world of sound that I'm fascinated by, and also sometimes get a different perspective on memories and emotions I've been mulling over that they find voice in these songs\".<ref name=\"abc.net.au\"/>\n\nGotye revealed that the second single from the album, \"Somebody That I Used to Know\", was not lyrically the result of a single break-up. \"It wasn't about one specific relationship,\" explained De Backer in an interview, \"but it was definitely drawn from various experiences I've had in relationships breaking up, and in the parts of the more reflective parts of the song, in the after-math and the memory of those different relationships and what they were and how they broke up and what's going on in everyone's minds. Yeah, so it's an amalgam of different feelings but not completely made up as such.\"<ref name=\"abc.net.au\"/>\n\nDespite the album's huge success, Gotye revealed in an interview with ''[[Rolling Stone Australia]]'' that he initially battled with indecision and depression while making the album, which in turn became the subject matter of songs like \"Smoke and Mirrors\" (with a central theme of [[impostor syndrome]]) and \"Save Me\". He stated: \"There were points that I thought I wouldn't be able to finish a record I was really into or that I'd give up at some stage.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Treuen |first=Jason |url=http://jasontreuen.wordpress.com/2011/10/30/rolling-stone-gotyes-mad-world/ |title=Rolling Stone: Gotye's Mad World |work=[[Rolling Stone Australia]] |date=30 October 2011 |accessdate=30 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nAccording to an interview in ''The Age'', the track \"State of the Art\" is about a secondhand 1970s organ Gotye's parents purchased. The accompanying music video is an animation showing a family purchasing and playing the instrument.\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| ADM = 6.6/10<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/review/3590/Gotye-Making-Mirrors.aspx |title=Making Mirrors by Gotye reviews |publisher=[[AnyDecentMusic?]] |accessdate=28 December 2019}}</ref>\n| MC = 69/100<ref name=\"MC\"/>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |last=O'Brien |first=Jon |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/making-mirrors-mw0002204056 |title=Making Mirrors \u2013 Gotye |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=3 June 2012}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Patrick |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/cdreviews/9071618/Gotye-Making-Mirrors-CD-review.html |title=Gotye: Making Mirrors, CD review |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=9 February 2012 |accessdate=3 June 2012 |location=London}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev3Score = B+<ref>{{cite web |last1=Anderson |first1=Kyle |last2=Rahman |first2=Ray |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2012/01/27/albums-feb-3-2012 |title=Albums: Feb. 3, 2012 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=27 January 2012 |accessdate=19 April 2012}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite news |last=Sullivan |first=Caroline |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2012/feb/09/gotye-making-mirrors-review |title=Gotye: Making Mirrors \u2013 review |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=9 February 2012 |accessdate=3 June 2012 |location=London}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[The Independent]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite news |last=Gill |first=Andy |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-gotye-making-mirrors-island-6699391.html |title=Album: Gotye, Making Mirrors (Island) |work=[[The Independent]] |date=10 February 2012 |accessdate=19 April 2012 |location=London |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120910154833/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-gotye-making-mirrors-island-6699391.html |archivedate=10 September 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev6Score = 5/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Malone |first=Ailbhe |url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/gotye/12711 |title=Gotye \u2013 'Making Mirrors' |work=[[NME]] |date=10 February 2012 |accessdate=19 April 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305070624/http://www.nme.com/reviews/gotye/12711 |archivedate=5 March 2016}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev7Score = 7.7/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Love |first=Joshua |url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/15749-making-mirrors/ |title=Gotye: Making Mirrors |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=9 September 2011 |accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |title=Gotye: Making Mirrors |work=[[Q (magazine)|Q]] |issue=309 |date=April 2012 |page=107}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev9Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |last=Rosen |first=Jody |authorlink=Jody Rosen |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/making-mirrors-20120214 |title=Making Mirrors |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=14 February 2012 |accessdate=19 April 2012}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]''\n| rev10Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal |title=Gotye: Making Mirrors |work=[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]] |issue=178 |date=March 2012 |page=87}}</ref>\n}}\n''Making Mirrors'' received generally positive reviews from music critics. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[standard score|normalised]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the album received an [[weighted mean|average]] score of 69, based on 19 reviews, which indicates \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/making-mirrors |title=Reviews for Making Mirrors by Gotye |publisher=[[Metacritic]]. [[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=3 June 2012}}</ref> Caitlin Welsh of ''[[The Music Network]]'' gave the album a favourable review, saying that it was \"just as rich, cheeky and steeped in pop history and musicality as its predecessor and as {{Sic|hide=y|carefully|-}}constructed and addictive as its breakout track ('[[Somebody That I Used to Know]]'), it will cement Wally de Backer as the oddball, everyman genius of Australian pop.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Welsh |first=Caitlin |url=http://www.themusicnetwork.com/reviews/album/2011/08/19/Gotye-Making-Mirrors/ |title=Album Review: Gotye, Making Mirrors |work=The Music Network |publisher=Peer Group Media |date=19 August 2011}}</ref> ''The Herald Sun'' gave it four out of five stars, adding that \"''Bronte'' and ''Giving Me a Chance'' are the latest in a long line of beautiful, visual songs begging to soundtrack the pivotal scene in a movie that's yet to be made.\"<ref name=\"heraldsun.com.au\">{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/music/album-review-making-mirrors-by-gotye-elevenuniversal/story-fn7oonq8-1226117613340 |title=Album review: Making Mirrors by Gotye (Eleven/Universal) |newspaper=Herald Sun |date=18 August 2011 |accessdate=10 February 2012}}</ref> Radar Radio also gave ''Making Mirrors'' four out of five stars and regarding the track \"Eyes Wide Open\" said, \"with lyrics like 'Some people offered up answers / We made out like we heard / but they were only words / They didn't add up to a change in the way we were living'. Now don't get me wrong, I have never been in a situation like this yet it feels so relatable.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radarradio.com.au/artists/reviews/gotye-making-mirrors-review.aspx |title=Gotye Making Mirrors Review &#124; Radar Artists. Band info, interviews, reviews & artist music upload |publisher=Radar Radio |accessdate=10 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007080854/http://www.radarradio.com.au/artists/reviews/gotye-making-mirrors-review.aspx |archivedate=7 October 2011 }}</ref> The album won the 2013 [[Grammy Award]] for [[Best Alternative Music Album]].\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = [[Gotye|Wally De Backer]]\n| title1   = Making Mirrors\n| length1  = 1:01\n| title2   = Easy Way Out\n| length2  = 1:57\n| title3   = [[Somebody That I Used to Know]]\n| note3    = featuring [[Kimbra]]\n| length3  = 4:04\n| title4   = [[Eyes Wide Open (Gotye song)|Eyes Wide Open]]\n| length4  = 3:11\n| title5   = Smoke and Mirrors\n| length5  = 5:13\n| title6   = [[I Feel Better (Gotye song)|I Feel Better]]\n| length6  = 3:18\n| title7   = In Your Light\n| length7  = 4:39\n| title8   = State of the Art\n| length8  = 5:22\n| title9   = Don't Worry, We'll Be Watching You\n| length9  = 3:18\n| title10  = Giving Me a Chance\n| length10 = 3:07\n| title11  = [[Save Me (Gotye song)|Save Me]]\n| length11 = 3:53\n| title12  = Bronte\n| length12 = 3:18\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Digital-only tracks\n| title13  = Dig Your Own Hole\n| length13 = 4:23\n| title14  = Showdown Below My Sombrero\n| length14 = 2:30\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Limited edition bonus DVD\n| title1   = The Making of Eyes Wide Open\n| note1    = documentary\n| length1  = 8:01\n| title2   = Making ''Making Mirrors''\n| note2    = documentary\n| length2  = 10:03\n| title3   = Eyes Wide Open\n| note3    = music video<!--They are called MUSIC VIDEOS, not 'film clips'. That's an unofficial title and is inconsistent with Wikipedia-wide terming-->\n| length3  = 3:18\n| title4   = Somebody That I Used to Know\n| note4    = featuring Kimbra) (music video\n| length4  = 4:03\n| title5   = State of the Art\n| note5    = music video\n| length5  = 5:18\n| title6   = Bronte\n| note6    = music video\n| length6  = 3:14\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n*Wally De Backer \u2013 lead and backing vocals, songwriter, samples, instruments\n*Francois Tetaz \u2013 dubs and spaces on \"Making Mirrors\"\n*Lucas Taranto \u2013 bass guitar on \"Easy Way Out\", \"Somebody That I Used to Know\", \"I Feel Better\", \"Save Me\", poker bass on \"Eyes Wide Open\", fretless bass on \"Bronte\"\n*Kimbra \u2013 lead and backing vocals on \"Somebody That I Used to Know\"\n*Gareth Skinner \u2013 whale cellos on \"Eyes Wide Open\"\n*Michael Hubbard \u2013 [[pedal steel guitar]] on \"Eyes Wide Open\"\n*Luke Hodgson \u2013 bass guitar on \"I Feel Better\"\n*Scott Tinkler \u2013 trumpet on \"In Your Light\"\n*Adam Simmons \u2013 saxophone on \"In Your Light\"\n*Frank De Backer \u2013 album artwork\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (2011\u201312)\n!scope=\"col\"|Peak<br>position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[ARIA Charts|Australian Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Gotye&titel=Making+Mirrors&cat=a |title=Gotye \u2013 Making Mirrors |publisher=australian-charts.com. Hung Medien |accessdate=20 September 2011}}</ref>\n|1\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[\u00d63 Austria Top 40|Austrian Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://austriancharts.at/showitem.asp?interpret=Gotye&titel=Making+Mirrors&cat=a |title=Gotye \u2013 Making Mirrors |publisher=austriancharts.at. Hung Medien |accessdate=12 January 2012}}</ref>\n|6\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[Ultratop|Belgian Albums Chart]] (Flanders)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ultratop.be/nl/showitem.asp?interpret=Gotye&titel=Making+Mirrors&cat=a |title=Gotye \u2013 Making Mirrors |language=Dutch |publisher=[[Ultratop]]. Hung Medien |ac