sements-Annuels.html?year=2012 |archivedate=14 October 2013 }}</ref>\n|18\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|German Albums Chart<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.viva.tv/charts/54-viva-jahrescharts-2012-album?page=5 |title=VIVA Jahrescharts 2012 Album |language=German |publisher=[[VIVA (TV station)|VIVA]]. [[Viacom International Media Networks (Europe)|Viacom International Media Networks]] |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6FjV7JkUf?url=http://www.viva.tv/charts/54-viva-jahrescharts-2012-album?page=5 |archivedate=8 April 2013 |accessdate=5 January 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|48\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Italian Albums Chart<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sorrisi.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/Top100_album_2012.pdf |title=Top 100 Album Combined \u2013 Classifica annuale (dal 2 Gennaio 2012 al 30 Dicembre 2012) |language=Italian |publisher=[[Federazione Industria Musicale Italiana]]. [[TV Sorrisi e Canzoni]] |accessdate=16 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6DiKI87yH?url=http://www.sorrisi.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/Top100_album_2012.pdf |archivedate=16 January 2013 }}</ref>\n|40\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Polish Albums Chart<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zpav.pl/rankingi/listy/top100/roczna.php?lang=2 |title=Top 100 \u2013 annual chart: 2012 |publisher=[[Polish Society of the Phonographic Industry|ZPAV]] |accessdate=15 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927134131/http://zpav.pl/rankingi/listy/top100/roczna.php?lang=2 |archivedate=27 September 2013 }}</ref>\n|9\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Swiss Albums Chart<ref>{{cite web |url=http://swisscharts.com/year.asp?key=2012 |title=Swiss Year-End Charts 2012 |publisher=swisscharts.com. Hung Medien |accessdate=4 January 2013}}</ref>\n|38\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''Billboard'' 200<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2012/the-billboard-200?begin=21&order=position |title=Billboard 200 Albums \u2013 2012 Year End Charts |work=Billboard |publisher=Prometheus Global Media |accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref>\n|27\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US Alternative Albums<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2012/top-alternative-albums |title=Alternative Albums \u2013 2012 Year End Charts |work=Billboard |publisher=Prometheus Global Media |accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref>\n|6\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US Rock Albums<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2012/top-rock-albums |title=Rock Albums \u2013 2012 Year End Charts |work=Billboard |publisher=Prometheus Global Media |accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref>\n|6\n|}\n\n===Decade-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (2010\u20132019)\n!scope=\"col\"|Position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Australian Albums (ARIA)<ref name=\"ARIAEndofDecade\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ariacharts.com.au/annual-charts/2019/end-of-decade-albums-chart|title= 2019 ARIA End of Decade Albums Chart|date=January 2020|accessdate=17 January 2020}}</ref>\n| 27\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Australian Artist Albums (ARIA)<ref name=\"ARIAEndofDecade\"/>\n| 3\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| US ''Billboard'' 200<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/decade-end/billboard-200|title=Decade-End Charts: Billboard 200|work=Billboard|accessdate=26 November 2019}}</ref>\n|177\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{certification Table Top}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=album|region=Australia|artist=Gotye|title=Making Mirrors|award=Platinum|number=3|certyear=2012|relyear=2011|accessdate=9 September 2019}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=album|region=Austria|artist=Gotye|title=Making Mirrors|award=Gold|certyear=2012|relyear=2011|accessdate=9 September 2019}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=album|region=Belgium|artist=Gotye|title=Making Mirrors|award=Platinum|certyear=2011|relyear=2011|accessdate=9 September 2019}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=album|region=Canada|artist=Gotye|title=Making Mirrors|award=Gold|certyear=2012|relyear=2011|accessdate=9 September 2019}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=album|region=Denmark|artist=Gotye|title=Making Mirrors|award=Gold|certyear=2012|relyear=2011|relmonth=9|accessdate=9 September 2019}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=album|region=France|artist=Gotye|title=Making Mirrors|award=Platinum|certyear=2012|relyear=2011|accessdate=9 September 2019}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=album|region=Germany|artist=Gotye|title=Making Mirrors|award=Gold|certyear=2012|relyear=2011|accessdate=9 September 2019}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=album|region=Italy|artist=Gotye|title=Making Mirrors|award=Gold|certyear=2012|relyear=2011|accessdate=9 September 2019}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=album|region=Netherlands|artist=Gotye|title=Making Mirrors|award=Gold|certyear=2012|relyear=2011|accessdate=9 September 2019}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=album|region=Poland|artist=Gotye|title=Making Mirrors|award=Platinum|number=2|certyear=2012|relyear=2011|accessdate=9 September 2019}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=album|region=United Kingdom|artist=Gotye|title=Making Mirrors|award=Gold|certyear=2012|relyear=2011|accessdate=9 September 2019}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=album|region=United States|artist=Gotye|title=Making Mirrors|award=Gold|certyear=2012|relyear=2011|accessdate=9 September 2019}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n\n==Appearances in media==\n* \"Don't Worry, We'll Be Watching You\" appears in the season 2 episode of ''[[Arrow (TV series)|Arrow]]'' titled \"Blast Radius\", in a scene in which Thea confronts Roy in the storeroom of Oliver's club.\n* \"Smoke and Mirrors\" appears in the season 1 episode of ''[[Ringer (TV series)|Ringer]]'' titled \"That Woman's Never Been a Victim Her Entire Life\", in a scene where Solomon searches Olivia's apartment.\n* \"Smoke and Mirrors\" appears in the season 2 episode of ''[[Suits (U.S. TV series)|Suits]]'' titled \"She knows\", in two scenes where Mike walks into the office and when he goes to the restaurant to meet Jessica.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of number-one albums of 2011 (Australia)]]\n* [[List of number-one albums of 2012 (Poland)]]\n* [[List of number-one Billboard Alternative Albums of 2012]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* ''[http://www.metacritic.com/music/making-mirrors/critic-reviews Making Mirrors]'' at [[Metacritic]]\n* {{YouTube|2ZXLyeatI0s|Making ''Making Mirrors'' \u2013 a short documentary}}\n\n{{Gotye}}\n{{ARIA Award for Album of the Year 2010s}}\n\n[[Category:2011 albums]]\n[[Category:ARIA Award-winning albums]]\n[[Category:Eleven: A Music Company albums]]\n[[Category:Gotye albums]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award for Best Alternative Music Album]]\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Making_Mirrors"}
{"title_page": "Andrea Dunbar", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name        = Andrea Dunbar\n| image       = Andrea_Dunbar_playwright.jpg\n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = 22 May 1961\n| birth_place = [[Bradford]], [[West Riding of Yorkshire]], England\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1990|12|20|1961|05|22}}\n| death_place = Bradford, [[West Yorkshire]], England\n| occupation  = Playwright\n| movement    = [[Realism (theatre)|Realism]]\n}}\n'''Andrea Dunbar''' (22 May 1961 \u2013 20 December 1990) was an English playwright. She wrote ''The Arbor'' (1980) and ''Rita, Sue and Bob Too'' (1982), an autobiographical drama about the sexual adventures of teenage girls living in a run-down part of [[Bradford]], West Yorkshire. She wrote most of the adaptation for the film ''[[Rita, Sue and Bob Too]]'' (1987). ''[[The Mail on Sunday]]'' described Dunbar as \"a genius straight from the slums\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Andrea Dunbar |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/60676 |website=oxforddnb.com |accessdate=13 November 2017 |url-access=subscription}} {{ODNBsub|sentence=yes}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Youngs |first=Ian |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-48348751 |title=The teenage Bradford 'genius' who told it like it was |work=BBC News |date=28 May 2019 |accessdate=28 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nDunbar was raised on Brafferton Arbor on the [[Buttershaw]] [[council estate]] in Bradford<ref name = \"telegraph\">{{cite web |url= http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/4582531.Life_of_playwright_will_hit_big_screen/\n|title=Friends to star in Dunbar's years on Bradford's Buttershaw Estate |last=Clayton |first=Emma |date=4 September 2009 |accessdate=18 May 2011 |work=The Bradford Telegraph & Argus}}</ref> with seven brothers and sisters. Both her parents had worked in the [[textile industry]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Bunting |first=Madeleine |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2010/oct/17/social-deprivation-in-britain-andrea-dunbar-arbor|title=Social deprivation in Britain: how a writer's life turned to tragedy |work=The Guardian|date=18 October 2010 |accessdate=28 May 2019}}</ref> Dunbar attended [[Buttershaw Comprehensive School]].\n\n==Career==\nDunbar began her first play ''The Arbor'' in 1977 at the age of 15,<ref name=\"guardian-hickling\">{{cite web |first1=Alfred |last1=Hickling |title=Back to Bradford: Andrea Dunbar remembered on film |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2010/apr/12/theatre |work=The Guardian |date=12 April 2010 |accessdate=13 November 2018}}</ref> writing it as a classroom assignment for [[Certificate of Secondary Education|CSE]] English. It is the story of \"a Bradford schoolgirl who falls pregnant to her Pakistani boyfriend on a racist estate,\" and has an abusive drunken father.<ref name=\"guardian-hickling\"/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Gardner |first=Lyn |title=Theatre review: The Arbor |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2001/jun/07/artsfeatures |work=The Guardian|date=6 June 2001 |accessdate=14 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Gilbey |first=Ryan |title=The Arbor (15) |url=https://www.newstatesman.com/film/2010/10/lorraine-dunbar-arbor-life |work=New Statesman |date=21 October 2010 |accessdate=14 November 2018}}</ref> Encouraged by her teacher, she was helped to develop the play to performance standard.<ref>[http://www.ipv.pt/forumedia/5/11.htm Katherine Anne Limmer, \"Investigating the Authority of the Literary Text in Critical Debate\".] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061031235634/http://www.ipv.pt/forumedia/5/11.htm |date=31 October 2006 }}</ref> It received its premi\u00e8re in 1980 at London's [[Royal Court Theatre]], directed by [[Max Stafford-Clark]].<ref name=\"guardian-hickling\"/> At age 18, Dunbar was the youngest playwright to have her work performed there.<ref>{{cite news |title=Dying daughter calls for memorial to mum |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-leeds-41608470 |work=BBC News|date=16 October 2017|accessdate=14 November 2018}}</ref> Alongside a play entered by Lucy Anderson Jones, ''The Arbor'' jointly won at the Young Writers' Festival, and was later augmented and performed in New York City.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rich |first=Frank |title=Theater: 'The Arbor,' From Britain |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/09/21/theater/theater-the-arbor-from-britain.html |work=The New York Times|date=21 September 1983 |accessdate=14 November 2018}}</ref> On 26 March 1980, she was featured in the BBC's ''[[Arena (UK TV series)|Arena]]'' arts documentary series.\n\nDunbar was quickly commissioned to write a follow-up play, ''Rita, Sue and Bob Too'', first performed in 1982. This explores similar themes to ''The Arbor'' through the lives of two teenage girls who are having affairs with the same married man. Dunbar's third play, ''Shirley'' (1986), places greater emphasis on a central character.<ref>Susan Carlson, ''Process and Product: Contemporary British Theatre and its Communities of Women'', Theatre Research International (1988), 13: pp 249\u2013263.</ref> It depicts a girl's \"tumultuous relationship\" with her mother. As she explained, she meant to write \"about Shirley and John but, you know, I wrote the mother in and she bloody took over the whole play.\"<ref>Virginia Blain, Patricia Clements and Isobel Grundy: ''The Feminist Companion to Literature in English. Women Writers from the Middle Ages to the Present Day'' (London: Batsford, 1990), p. 315.</ref>\n\nThe film version of ''[[Rita, Sue and Bob Too]]'' (1987) was adapted for the cinema by Dunbar, directed by [[Alan Clarke]] and filmed on the Buttershaw estate. Dunbar disowned the film when more writers were brought in to give it a happier ending.<ref name=\"guardian-hickling\"/> However, it created considerable controversy on the estate because of its negative portrayal of the area.<ref name=\"guardian-hickling\"/> Dunbar was threatened by several residents, but nevertheless continued to live there.<ref name=\"guardian-hickling\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nDunbar first became pregnant at age 15; the baby was stillborn at 6 months.<ref name=\"artangel\">\"[http://www.artangel.org.uk//projects/2010/the_arbor/lyn_gardner_on_andrea_dunbar/lyn_gardner_on_andrea_dunbar Lyn Gardner, Born to Write and Die\"]. The Guardian, 4 July 1998.</ref> She later had three children by three different fathers. The first, Lorraine, was born in 1979, and had a Pakistani father.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Johnston|first=Sheila|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/starsandstories/8066286/The-Arbor-examining-Andrea-Dunbars-legacy.html|title=The Arbor: examining Andrea Dunbar's legacy|date=2010-10-18|access-date=2020-04-18|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> A year later, in 1980, Lisa was born, again while Dunbar was still a teenager.<ref name=\"bbcfootsteps\">\"[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-11581747 Liam Allen, The Arbor: In the footsteps of Rita, Sue and Bob\"]. BBC News, 22 October 2010.</ref> About three years later, she had a son, Andrew, with Jim Wheeler.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://northernlifemagazine.co.uk/rita-sue-and-bob-too-30-years-on-andrea-dunbar/|title=http://northernlifemagazine.co.uk/rita-sue-and-bob-too-30-years-on-andrea-dunbar/|last=Davis|first=Mark|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artangel.org.uk/the-arbor/born-to-write-and-die/|title=Artangel|website=artangel.org.uk|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\nAs a single mother, Dunbar spent 18 months in a [[Women's Aid Federation of England|Women's Aid]] refuge and became an increasingly heavy drinker. In 1990 she died of a [[Cerebral hemorrhage|brain haemorrhage]] at the age of 29 after becoming ill in ''The Beacon'', a pub in Reevy Road and a location seen in the opening shot of ''Rita, Sue and Bob Too''.\n\nIn 2007 her eldest daughter Lorraine, a heroin addict at the time, was convicted of [[manslaughter]] for causing the death of her child by gross neglect after the child ingested a lethal dose of [[methadone]].<ref name =\"indie\">[http://www.indiewire.com/article/tribeca_10_clio_barnards_the_arbor_defies_categorization/ Tribeca '10 |Clio Barnard's \"The Arbor\" Defies Categorization, ''Indiewire'', 10 April 2010.]</ref><ref name=\"guardian1\">Martin Wainwright, \"[https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2007/nov/24/theatrenews.theatre Playwright's darkest visions return to consume her family]\". The Guardian, 24 November 2007.</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, her daughter Lisa died of cancer after having been diagnosed in December 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/15810911.andrea-dunbars-daughter-lisa-pearce-dies/|title=Andrea Dunbar's \"force of nature\" daughter dies|website=Bradford Telegraph and Argus|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\n==Depictions==\nIn 2000, Dunbar's life and her surroundings were revisited in the play ''A State Affair'' by [[Robin Soans]].<ref>''Rita, Sue and Bob Too'' by Andrea Dunbar/''A State Affair'' by Robin Soans, Methuen Books, 2000, {{ISBN|0-413-75700-5}}</ref>\n\nA film about her life, ''The Arbor'', directed by [[Clio Barnard]], was released in 2010.<ref name=\"guardian-hickling\"/> The film uses actors lip-synching to interviews with Dunbar and her family, and concentrates on the strained relationship between Dunbar and her daughter Lorraine.<ref name=\"guardian-hickling\"/><ref name = \"telegraph\"/> The film was nominated for a [[64th British Academy Film Awards#Outstanding Debut by a British Director|BAFTA]] award for Outstanding Debut by a British Director, and won the [[Sutherland Trophy]], at the 2010 [[London Film Festival Awards]]. It also won the Sheffield Innovation Award at the 2010 [[Sheffield Doc/Fest]].\n\nA novel inspired by Dunbar's life and work, ''Black Teeth and a Brilliant Smile'' by [[Adelle Stripe]], was published in 2017 by [[Wrecking Ball Press]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pressreader.com/uk/yorkshire-post/20170522/281801398901103 |title=PressReader.com \u2013 Connecting People Through News|publisher=pressreader.com |accessdate=23 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-leeds-39973767 |title=Rita, Sue and Bob Too: A snapshot of 1980s Britain |date=29 May 2017 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=23 June 2017 }}</ref> shortlisted for the [[Gordon Burn Prize]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thebookseller.com/news/denise-mina-makes-gordon-burn-prize-shortlist-595326|title=Denise Mina makes Gordon Burn Prize shortlist {{!}} The Bookseller |website=thebookseller.com |accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref> and gained the [[Society of Authors]]' K Blundell Trust Award for Fiction.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://societyofauthors.org/News/News/2016/December/Authors-Awards-December-2016 |title=News {{!}} The Society of Authors |website=societyofauthors.org |accessdate=23 June 2017}}</ref> A second edition came from [[Fleet Publishing]] in the same year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thebookseller.com/news/fleet-acquires-andrea-dunbar-inspired-kitchen-sink-noir-631081 |title=ANDREA DUNBAR-INSPIRED NOVEL TO FLEET {{!}} |website=bookseller.com |accessdate=10 September 2017}}</ref> In 2019 a stage adaptation by Freedom Studios and screenwriter Lisa Holdsworth was announced in ''[[The Guardian]]''. Dramatisation of Stripe's \"strikingly atmospheric novel\" will focus on women's relationships, with a cast of five sharing the roles. It shows a teenage Dunbar rising to national note with her autobiographical works ''The Arbor'' and ''Rita, Sue and Bob Too'', and the challenges of life on the [[Buttershaw]] estate in [[Bradford]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Wiegand |first=Chris |url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2018/dec/10/andrea-dunbar-playwright-life-story-bradford-rita-sue-bob-too |title=Andrea Dunbar's life story to be staged in Bradford pub |date=10 December 2018 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=7 January 2019 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0241816|Andrea Dunbar}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dunbar, Andrea}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:1990 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Bradford]]\n[[Category:20th-century British dramatists and playwrights]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name        = Andrea Dunbar\n| image       = Andrea_Dunbar_playwright.jpg\n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = 22 May 1961\n| birth_place = [[Bradford]], [[West Riding of Yorkshire]], England\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1990|12|20|1961|05|22}}\n| death_place = Bradford, [[West Yorkshire]], England\n| occupation  = Playwright\n| movement    = [[Realism (theatre)|Realism]]\n}}\n'''Andrea Dunbar''' (22 May 1961 \u2013 20 December 1990) was an English playwright. She wrote ''The Arbor'' (1980) and ''Rita, Sue and Bob Too'' (1982), an autobiographical drama about the sexual adventures of teenage girls living in a run-down part of [[Bradford]], West Yorkshire. She wrote most of the adaptation for the film ''[[Rita, Sue and Bob Too]]'' (1987). ''[[The Mail on Sunday]]'' described Dunbar as \"a genius straight from the slums\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Andrea Dunbar |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/60676 |website=www.oxforddnb.com |accessdate=13 November 2017 |url-access=subscription}} {{ODNBsub|sentence=yes}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Youngs |first=Ian |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-48348751 |title=The teenage Bradford 'genius' who told it like it was |work=BBC News |date=28 May 2019 |accessdate=28 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nDunbar was raised on Brafferton Arbor on the [[Buttershaw]] [[council estate]] in Bradford<ref name = \"telegraph\">{{cite web |url= http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/4582531.Life_of_playwright_will_hit_big_screen/\n|title=Friends to star in Dunbar's years on Bradford's Buttershaw Estate |last=Clayton |first=Emma |date=4 September 2009 |accessdate=18 May 2011 |work=The Bradford Telegraph & Argus}}</ref> with seven brothers and sisters. Both her parents had worked in the [[textile industry]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Bunting |first=Madeleine |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2010/oct/17/social-deprivation-in-britain-andrea-dunbar-arbor|title=Social deprivation in Britain: how a writer's life turned to tragedy |work=The Guardian|date=18 October 2010 |accessdate=28 May 2019}}</ref> Dunbar attended [[Buttershaw Comprehensive School]].\n\n==Career==\nDunbar began her first play ''The Arbor'' in 1977 at the age of 15,<ref name=\"guardian-hickling\">{{cite web |first1=Alfred |last1=Hickling |title=Back to Bradford: Andrea Dunbar remembered on film |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2010/apr/12/theatre |work=The Guardian |date=12 April 2010 |accessdate=13 November 2018}}</ref> writing it as a classroom assignment for [[Certificate of Secondary Education|CSE]] English. It is the story of \"a Bradford schoolgirl who falls pregnant to her Pakistani boyfriend on a racist estate,\" and has an abusive drunken father.<ref name=\"guardian-hickling\"/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Gardner |first=Lyn |title=Theatre review: The Arbor |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2001/jun/07/artsfeatures |work=The Guardian|date=6 June 2001 |accessdate=14 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Gilbey |first=Ryan |title=The Arbor (15) |url=https://www.newstatesman.com/film/2010/10/lorraine-dunbar-arbor-life |work=New Statesman |date=21 October 2010 |accessdate=14 November 2018}}</ref> Encouraged by her teacher, she was helped to develop the play to performance standard.<ref>[http://www.ipv.pt/forumedia/5/11.htm Katherine Anne Limmer, \"Investigating the Authority of the Literary Text in Critical Debate\".] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061031235634/http://www.ipv.pt/forumedia/5/11.htm |date=31 October 2006 }}</ref> It received its premi\u00e8re in 1980 at London's [[Royal Court Theatre]], directed by [[Max Stafford-Clark]].<ref name=\"guardian-hickling\"/> At age 18, Dunbar was the youngest playwright to have her work performed there.<ref>{{cite news |title=Dying daughter calls for memorial to mum |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-leeds-41608470 |work=BBC News|date=16 October 2017|accessdate=14 November 2018}}</ref> Alongside a play entered by Lucy Anderson Jones, ''The Arbor'' jointly won at the Young Writers' Festival, and was later augmented and performed in New York City.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rich |first=Frank |title=Theater: 'The Arbor,' From Britain |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/09/21/theater/theater-the-arbor-from-britain.html |work=The New York Times|date=21 September 1983 |accessdate=14 November 2018}}</ref> On 26 March 1980, she was featured in the BBC's ''[[Arena (UK TV series)|Arena]]'' arts documentary series.\n\nDunbar was quickly commissioned to write a follow-up play, ''Rita, Sue and Bob Too'', first performed in 1982. This explores similar themes to ''The Arbor'' through the lives of two teenage girls who are having affairs with the same married man. Dunbar's third play, ''Shirley'' (1986), places greater emphasis on a central character.<ref>Susan Carlson, ''Process and Product: Contemporary British Theatre and its Communities of Women'', Theatre Research International (1988), 13: pp 249\u2013263.</ref> It depicts a girl's \"tumultuous relationship\" with her mother. As she explained, she meant to write \"about Shirley and John but, you know, I wrote the mother in and she bloody took over the whole play.\"<ref>Virginia Blain, Patricia Clements and Isobel Grundy: ''The Feminist Companion to Literature in English. Women Writers from the Middle Ages to the Present Day'' (London: Batsford, 1990), p. 315.</ref>\n\nThe film version of ''[[Rita, Sue and Bob Too]]'' (1987) was adapted for the cinema by Dunbar, directed by [[Alan Clarke]] and filmed on the Buttershaw estate. Dunbar disowned the film when more writers were brought in to give it a happier ending.<ref name=\"guardian-hickling\"/> However, it created considerable controversy on the estate because of its negative portrayal of the area.<ref name=\"guardian-hickling\"/> Dunbar was threatened by several residents, but nevertheless continued to live there.<ref name=\"guardian-hickling\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nDunbar first became pregnant at age 15; the baby was stillborn at 6 months.<ref name=\"artangel\">\"[http://www.artangel.org.uk//projects/2010/the_arbor/lyn_gardner_on_andrea_dunbar/lyn_gardner_on_andrea_dunbar Lyn Gardner, Born to Write and Die\"]. The Guardian, 4 July 1998.</ref> She later had three children by three different fathers. The first, Lorraine, was born in 1979, and had a Pakistani father.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Johnston|first=Sheila|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/starsandstories/8066286/The-Arbor-examining-Andrea-Dunbars-legacy.html|title=The Arbor: examining Andrea Dunbar's legacy|date=2010-10-18|access-date=2020-04-18|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> A year later, in 1980, Lisa was born, again while Dunbar was still a teenager.<ref name=\"bbcfootsteps\">\"[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-11581747 Liam Allen, The Arbor: In the footsteps of Rita, Sue and Bob\"]. BBC News, 22 October 2010.</ref> About three years later, she had a son, Andrew, with Jim Wheeler.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://northernlifemagazine.co.uk/rita-sue-and-bob-too-30-years-on-andrea-dunbar/|title=http://northernlifemagazine.co.uk/rita-sue-and-bob-too-30-years-on-andrea-dunbar/|last=Davis|first=Mark|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artangel.org.uk/the-arbor/born-to-write-and-die/|title=Artangel|website=www.artangel.org.uk|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\nAs a single mother, Dunbar spent 18 months in a [[Women's Aid Federation of England|Women's Aid]] refuge and became an increasingly heavy drinker. In 1990 she died of a [[Cerebral hemorrhage|brain haemorrhage]] at the age of 29 after becoming ill in ''The Beacon'', a pub in Reevy Road and a location seen in the opening shot of ''Rita, Sue and Bob Too''. \n\nIn 2007 her eldest daughter Lorraine, a heroin addict at the time, was convicted of [[manslaughter]] for causing the death of her child by gross neglect after the child ingested a lethal dose of [[methadone]].<ref name =\"indie\">[http://www.indiewire.com/article/tribeca_10_clio_barnards_the_arbor_defies_categorization/ Tribeca '10 |Clio Barnard's \"The Arbor\" Defies Categorization, ''Indiewire'', 10 April 2010.]</ref><ref name=\"guardian1\">Martin Wainwright, \"[https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2007/nov/24/theatrenews.theatre Playwright's darkest visions return to consume her family]\". The Guardian, 24 November 2007.</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, her daughter Lisa died of cancer after having been diagnosed in December 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/15810911.andrea-dunbars-daughter-lisa-pearce-dies/|title=Andrea Dunbar's \"force of nature\" daughter dies|website=Bradford Telegraph and Argus|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\n==Depictions==\nIn 2000, Dunbar's life and her surroundings were revisited in the play ''A State Affair'' by [[Robin Soans]].<ref>''Rita, Sue and Bob Too'' by Andrea Dunbar/''A State Affair'' by Robin Soans, Methuen Books, 2000, {{ISBN|0-413-75700-5}}</ref>\n\nA film about her life, ''The Arbor'', directed by [[Clio Barnard]], was released in 2010.<ref name=\"guardian-hickling\"/> The film uses actors lip-synching to interviews with Dunbar and her family, and concentrates on the strained relationship between Dunbar and her daughter Lorraine.<ref name=\"guardian-hickling\"/><ref name = \"telegraph\"/> The film was nominated for a [[64th British Academy Film Awards#Outstanding Debut by a British Director|BAFTA]] award for Outstanding Debut by a British Director, and won the [[Sutherland Trophy]], at the 2010 [[London Film Festival Awards]]. It also won the Sheffield Innovation Award at the 2010 [[Sheffield Doc/Fest]].\n\nA novel inspired by Dunbar's life and work, ''Black Teeth and a Brilliant Smile'' by [[Adelle Stripe]], was published in 2017 by [[Wrecking Ball Press]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pressreader.com/uk/yorkshire-post/20170522/281801398901103 |title=PressReader.com \u2013 Connecting People Through News|publisher=pressreader.com |accessdate=23 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-leeds-39973767 |title=Rita, Sue and Bob Too: A snapshot of 1980s Britain |date=29 May 2017 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=23 June 2017 }}</ref> shortlisted for the [[Gordon Burn Prize]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thebookseller.com/news/denise-mina-makes-gordon-burn-prize-shortlist-595326|title=Denise Mina makes Gordon Burn Prize shortlist {{!}} The Bookseller |website=www.thebookseller.com |accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref> and gained the [[Society of Authors]]' K Blundell Trust Award for Fiction.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://societyofauthors.org/News/News/2016/December/Authors-Awards-December-2016 |title=News {{!}} The Society of Authors |website=societyofauthors.org |accessdate=23 June 2017}}</ref> A second edition came from [[Fleet Publishing]] in the same year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thebookseller.com/news/fleet-acquires-andrea-dunbar-inspired-kitchen-sink-noir-631081 |title=ANDREA DUNBAR-INSPIRED NOVEL TO FLEET {{!}} |website=bookseller.com |accessdate=10 September 2017}}</ref> In 2019 a stage adaptation by Freedom Studios and screenwriter Lisa Holdsworth was announced in ''[[The Guardian]]''. Dramatisation of Stripe's \"strikingly atmospheric novel\" will focus on women's relationships, with a cast of five sharing the roles. It shows a teenage Dunbar rising to national note with her autobiographical works ''The Arbor'' and ''Rita, Sue and Bob Too'', and the challenges of life on the [[Buttershaw]] estate in [[Bradford]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Wiegand |first=Chris |url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2018/dec/10/andrea-dunbar-playwright-life-story-bradford-rita-sue-bob-too |title=Andrea Dunbar's life story to be staged in Bradford pub |date=10 December 2018 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=7 January 2019 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0241816|Andrea Dunbar}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dunbar, Andrea}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:1990 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Bradford]]\n[[Category:20th-century British dramatists and playwrights]]\n", "name_user": "Kahtar", "label": "safe", "comment": "Repair CS1 error(s), replaced: website=www. \u2192 website= (3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrea_Dunbar"}
